<HEADLINE> Earth Faces Exhaustion as World Economies Grow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 11 (Xinhua) - Unprecedented world economic
growth is beginning to "hit the wall" of what the earth's natural
systems can stand, an authoritative report said.
</P>
<P>
The report, published by the Worldwatch on Sunday, said the
global economy has grown by 5 trillion US dollars in the past
seven years, more than in the entire 10000 years between the birth
of agriculture and the end of the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
It said that global output of goods and services has grown
almost sixfold since 1950. Last year's growth, of 1.1 trillion US
dollars, exceeded the growth in output throughout the world during
the entire 17th century.
</P>
<P>
If it continues to grow at this rate, it will almost double
from 29 trillion US dollars today to 57 trillion US dollars in
2020, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The State of the World Report warned that the world economy
"has begun to outrun the capacity of the earth to supply basic
goods and services".
</P>
<P>
It suggested that instead of trying to halt growth, greater use
should be made of renewable energy, such as wind power, to allow
the economy to continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
The report echoes warnings by environmentalists 25 years ago of
limits to so-called renewable resources such as water and soil.
</P>
<P>
"Over the last half century", said the report, "the use of wood
almost doubled, that of paper increased nearly sixfold, fish
consumption increased fivefold, water use tripled, grain
consumption nearly tripled, steel use increased fourfold, and
fossil fuel consumption increased nearly fivefold."
</P>
<P>
Yet, unlike early environmentalists, the report does not
advocate ending growth, merely redirecting it, saying whereas the
threat of global warming places a limit on growth based on fossil
fuels, it can continue for much longer if based on renewable
energy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
