<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 18 Airlines Denied Permits in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Only nine out of 27 airlines
were issued with operating permits in Zambia in 1977, compared to
25 in the previous year, Sunday Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper quoted a parliamentary report as saying
that the 18 airlines have not met several basic requirements for
establishing an airline.
</P>
<P>
One of the requirements is to have Zambians as majority
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
Other conditions include arranging for the inspection of the
aircraft to be used and the maintenance base, providing
information on who would carry out aircraft maintenance,
advertising in the government gazette, the intention to register
the company with the Ministry of Commerce, Trade and Industry and
applying to the Ministry of Communications and Transport for an
operating air service permit.
</P>
<P>
Until 1991, Zambia did not have an open sky policy and then
the state-run Zambia Airways enjoyed the monopoly of all routes.
</P>
<P>
The private sector has since filled the vacuum left by the
liquidated Zambia Airways on domestic and international routes.
</P>
<P>
But the parliament committee on social services has noted that
the aviation industry is in turmoil exacerbated by numerous
squabbles among the local airlines.
</P>
<P>
Another negative factor affecting the air transport industry
is that the fledgling airlines are unable to mount long haul
flights, the paper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
