<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerians Concern over Poor Navigation Aids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Domestic air travellers in
Nigeria have expressed concern over the obsolete state of
navigation aids in the country's airports, which led to a
paralysis of air travel last week following the Harmattan haze.
</P>
<P>
Many flights were disrupted last week with the intensification
of the Harmattan, the seasonal hot, dry and dust-laden wind from
the Sahara which causes poor visibility, making it difficult for
flights to take off and land at the airports.
</P>
<P>
Some air travellers have complained that if the navigation
aids were functional, it would have been possible for flights to
take off and land safely despite the poor visibility, the News
Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
Last year, th International Federation of Aviation Line Pilots
Association classified the navigation aids as "critically
deficient" at the country's major airports in Kano, Lagos and
Port Harcourt.
</P>
<P>
However, the equipment is functioning well at Lagos
International Airport where flights to and from foreign countries
have not been affected by the Harmattan haze so far this year.
</P>
<P>
To improve the poor situation, the federal airports authority
of Nigeria has placed orders for 21 instrument landing system for
19 airports in the country, the news agency said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
