<HEADLINE> OIC Condemns Israeli Settlement Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of the
Islamic Conference (OIC) today strongly condemned Israel for the
construction of new settlements near Jerusalem and on occupied
Arab lands, reports reaching here from Jeddah, Saudi Arabia, said.
</P>
<P>
The Jeddah-based OIC demanded in a statement that peace-loving
nations take necessary measures to stop the Israeli settlements
and resume the peace process according to the agreements signed
between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Israel announced last Thursday a government decision to build
600 new homes in two West Bank settlements.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Israel's Housing Ministry is working on plans
to build 30,200 additional homes for Jews in the West Bank, nearly
doubling the number of settlers in the occupied territory.
</P>
<P>
Most of the new housing is to be built within 15 kilometers of
Jerusalem, an area which the right-wing government of Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has said will never be ceded to
Palestinian rule.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu this week vowed to forge ahead with construction of
Jewish homes in the West Bank and Gaza Strip in defiance of
Palestinian and U.S. demands for a freeze pending the outcome of
negotiations on a final status agreement for the occupied
territories.
</P>
<P>
The new settlements constitute an Israeli challenge to the
international community at a time when intensified efforts are
being made to overcome the stalemate in the peace process, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Jewish settlement policy pursued by the Israeli government
has been hampering the concerned parties from achieving any
progress in the peace process, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
