<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia, Pakistan Coordinate on Afghan Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia and Pakistan
were trying to find a peaceful settlement of the civil war in
Afghanistan, sources from the Pakistani Embassy in Saudi Arabia
was reported as revealing today.
</P>
<P>
According to the Kuwait News Agency, Pakistani Foreign
Undersecretary Shamshad Ahmad, during a shuttle visit to Saudi
Arabia Saturday, coordinated with the Saudi government in a bid to
strengthen peace efforts in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The sources said the Pakistani government sought to inform
Riyadh on the outcome of the negotiations it recently held with
leaders of Afghan factions.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, Islamabad has recently received
separately deposed President Burhanuddin Rabbani and head of the
Taliban government Mullar Mohammad Ghowth who held talks with
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif on the possibility of
putting an end to the bloodletting in war-torn Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani's visit to Islamabad came following a meeting which he
held with Sharif in Tehran, Iran on the sidelines of the eighth
Islamic summit in December, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani undersecretary and Saudi Foreign Minister Prince
Saud Al-Faisal held a meeting Saturday to express support for
efforts to find a peaceful settlement to the Afghan problem, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan believes there are good chances to stop the protracted
war in Afghanistan during the holy month of Ramadan and the Afghan
factions have come to realize that war will not solve the problem,
the undersecretary said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Al-Faisal told the Pakistani envoy that Riyadh
fully supports all mediation efforts.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia and Pakistan were the first two countries that
formally recognized the Taliban government in May, 1997 soon after
the militia group took over the capital Kabul and declared to
represent Afghan people as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Three years ago, Pakistan and Saudi Arabia co-sponsored Afghan
national conciliation talks in Mecca, Saudi Arabia that led to a
short-lived cease-fire in Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
