<HEADLINE> New Political Party Registers in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 11 (Xinhua) -- A new centrist party came
into being today in Israel, with the probable defection of an
influential member from the ruling Likud party.
</P>
<P>
The party, named Atid (future), submitted its founding
documents signed by 140 members to the Registrar of political
Parties in Tel Aviv today to prepare for new elections, according
to Israel radio.
</P>
<P>
Member of the Likud, Ronni Milo, who is also Tel Aviv City
Mayor, was identified with Atid, but he himself did not sign the
founding documents.
</P>
<P>
Atid is said to be the centrist party in the country, which is
regarded as a ready-made political platform for Milo.
</P>
<P>
Milo, who has big differences with Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu on many issues, is particularly critical of Netanyahu's
leadership.
</P>
<P>
The Radio quoted several supporters of the Atid as saying that
the new party represents the political will of secular groups of
the country.
</P>
<P>
"We oppose the Likud party because it has made too much
concessions to the religious parties of the coalition in state
budget formulation and its hard-line policy towards the peace
process," they said.
</P>
<P>
"But at the same time we do not like the Labor party because it
had too much internal conflicts and struggle that occurred only
for personal reasons," they added.
</P>
<P>
The Radio commented that Milo's possible departure from the
Likud will definitely cause another political blow to Netanyahu,
who has just lost David levy, former foreign minister, due to
political differences between the them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
