<HEADLINE> Team Canada Leaves Without Chretien </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Team Canada left Sunday for its
fifth major trade mission abroad, this time without Prime Minister
Jean Chretien and two provincial premiers.
</P>
<P>
Chretien and premiers of Ontario and Quebec provinces will stay
home and lead emergency efforts in the two storm-ravaged provinces
where dozens of communities remain paralyzed and powerless.
</P>
<P>
The 13-day mission to Mexico, Brazil, Argentina and Chile
involves more than 500 politicians, civil servants and business
executives.
</P>
<P>
Chretien, who said he would join the mission later, boarded
Team Canada's chartered Boeing 747 to see off the delegation here
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The mission will be led by Canadian Governor General Romeo
LeBlanc until Chretien arrives.
</P>
<P>
Team Canada, an invention of the present Liberal Party
government, was designed to further Canada's international trade.
</P>
<P>
Up until now, its previous trips have been made primarily to
Asia, in 1994, '95 and '97 respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
