<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Denies Reported Large-scale Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu today denied reports that Israel is to build
large number of housing units in settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the denial at a weekly cabinet meeting today to
formulate the obligations the government is to require the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) to fulfill before carrying
out the second redeployment in West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The leading hardliner of the Israeli government, National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon criticized Netanyahu for what
he called as an unnecessary denial.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, considered to
be a dove, commended Natanyahu for clarifying government stance.
</P>
<P>
Israel was reportedly to build 30,000 housing units in
settlements in the West Bank. The news came after Israel's
approval Wednesday for building 600 housing units in the Efrat
settlement, south of the West Bank city of Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
Both the United States and the PNA have blasted Israel's plans
to expand settlements in the occupied territories as an obstacle
to revitalizing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued after today's Cabinet meeting said Netanyahu
also refuted threats of Intifada (Palestinian uprising) and
renewed violence issued by Palestinian officials recently.
</P>
<P>
He said threats of violence did not serve the readiness for
real peace and Israel is insisting that negotiations be held
peacefully and will not change this position as a result of
threats.
</P>
<P>
Today's cabinet meeting focus on drafting a list of commitments
which the PNA is required to undertake under under the Note for
Record attached to the Hebron Accord signed a year ago.
</P>
<P>
They included four general demands: completing the process of
revising the Palestinian Charter that calls for Israel's
destruction, fighting terror and preventing violence against
Israel, restricting the number of the Palestinian police force and
restricting PNA's activities in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The statement added that the Cabinet would hold another session
Tuesday to continue discussing the PNA commitments.
</P>
<P>
Under pressure of the United States, Netanyahu announced
Thursday that he would split the second Israeli redeployment in
the West Bank into two decisions.
</P>
<P>
The first on the pullback scope is to be made ahead of his
visit to Washington for talks with U.S. President Bill Clinton
later this month, while the second will be made five months later
on whether to carry out the pullback based on the PNA's
fulfillment of its commitments.
</P>
<P>
The move was seen as an attempt to further delay the troop
withdrawal in order to prevent hardliners within the stumbling
coalition from toppling the government.
</P>
<P>
The right-wingers have threatened to overthrow the government if
it returns an inch of West Bank land to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is also to meet PNA President Yasser Arafat in a bid to
move the peace process forward. Palestinians are disappointed with
the stalemate of the process and the "non-results" of U.S. envoy
Dennis Ross's recent visit to the region.
</P>
<P>
They warned that a failure of the Washington talks could lead
to renewed popular Palestinian uprising. 
</P>
</TEXT>
