<HEADLINE> French FM Arrives in Lebanon on Mideast Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 11 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine arrived here tonight on the first leg of his Middle East
tour aimed at reviving the stalled peace process and seeking a
larger role in the region.
</P>
<P>
During his 16-hour visit, Vedrine will hold talks with Lebanese
officials on the deadlocked peace process and the situation in
south Lebanon, especially the recent Israeli offer to
conditionally implement the U.N. Security Council Resolution 425.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. resolution calls for Israeli withdrawal from south
Lebanon and western Bekaa without conditions.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon had rejected the Israeli proposal, denouncing it as a
maneuver to drive a wedge between Syrian and Lebanese tracks in
the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
According to his schedule, Vedrine and his accompanying
delegation will meet with Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez Boueiz
soon after their arrival.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, Vedrine is expected to inaugurate the new French
consulate here.
</P>
<P>
Later, he will hold talks with Lebanese President Elias Hrawi,
House Speaker Nabih Berri and Prime Minister Rafik Hariri before
going on to Amman and Damascus.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources here said that during his Mideast tour,
Vedrine will reiterate France's support for building a
comprehensive and lasting peace in the region but his brief visit
is not expected to make any breakthrough. 
</P>
</TEXT>
