<HEADLINE> Zambia, Congo (K) Enhance Security Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Zambia and the Democratic
Republic of Congo have signed a defense protocol to enhance
security cooperation, Zambian Defense Minister Chitalu Sampa said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Sampa returned here today from his visit to Congo (K), where
he signed the protocol.
</P>
<P>
He said for many years the two countries had problems on the
common border areas including killings and smugglings.
</P>
<P>
It is impossible to settle the problems because of the nature
of the former government of Mobutu Sese Seko in former Zaire, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Since Laurent Kabila took power last year in that country, the
border areas have been very quiet for some time, and calm has
returned to border towns, Sampa said.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian minister said that he believed that all defense
issues and many other problems will be tackled quickly with the
establishment of a commission and the signing of the protocol of
understanding. 
</P>
</TEXT>
