<HEADLINE> Sudan Appeals for Relief for Southern Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Sudan appealed today to the
international community for relief for defected rebels and
civilians in the southern state of Bahr el-Ghazal.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference held here, Sudanese first Vice President
El-Zubeir Mohammed Saleh called on Sudan's brothers, friends and
neighbors to provide food and clothing.
</P>
<P>
He said that protracted fightings and poor agricultural seasons
have left thousands of former rebels and civilians in urgent need
for food and other daily necessities.
</P>
<P>
He said 8,000 rebels have defected in the state and that there
are more civilian returnees in the state.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese government reached a peace agreement with six
minor rebel factions in 1997. But the Sudan People's Liberation
Army (SPLA), the strongest rebel group, has rejected the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Saleh disclosed that the defected rebels have joined the
government forces to repel aggressions launched by the SPLA led by
John Garang.
</P>
<P>
He said the defection of the rebels is a victory of the peace
process, underlining that all the returnees have expressed full
support for the peace agreement and renounced the civil war.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese rebels took up arms to fight the Islamic
government since 1983 for more autonomy in the south, where the
population is mostly Christians and animists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
