<HEADLINE> Egyptian Celebrities Seek to Ease Iraqi Sufferings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 11 (Xinhua) -- A group of Egyptian celebrities
today launched a campaign to seek the help of the Arab League (AL)
to ease the sufferings of Iraqi children under the United Nations
sanctions, the Middle East News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The group asked AL Secretary General Esmat Abdel-Meguid in a
message to convince the U.N. to dispatch a plane carrying more
medicine to Iraq at the Ramadan Bairam late this month.
</P>
<P>
The group, led by Egypt's acclaimed film director Youssef
Chahine who won a special prize for his life's works at the Cannes
Film Festival in 1997, included actresses Raghda, writer Nawal
El-Saadawi as well as doctors and pharmacists.
</P>
<P>
They sent some 2.5 tonnes of medicine and gifts for Iraqi
children and the signatures of 1 million Egyptians to rally
support for Iraq during a visit to Baghdad a week ago.
</P>
<P>
The group also took an initiative to tour hospitals in Baghdad,
where they recognized the shortage of medicine and medical
equipment.
</P>
<P>
Arab League spokesman Talaat Hamed said the Arab organization
will ask the U.N. Sanctions Committee to agree to the humanitarian
request.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid will send a message to U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan and the Security Council to consider the request aimed to
ease the sufferings of the Iraqis, he added.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under crippling economic sanctions imposed by the
U.N. in 1990 after its invasion of Kuwait. 
</P>
</TEXT>
