<HEADLINE> Japanese Urge Immediate Halt to U.S. Night Drills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of local governments have
urged a prompt halt to the U.S. Navy's ongoing night landing
drills at three Japanese bases Monday, Kyodo news service reported.
</P>
<P>
The local administrative chiefs in Tokyo, Kanagawa and
Yamaguchi prefectures called for the cancellation of U.S. Navy
aircraft drills at air stations in Yokota in western Tokyo, Atsugi
in Kanagawa, and Iwakuni in Yamaichi which began Friday.
</P>
<P>
A liaison council of municipalities near the Yokota base in
Tokyo protested to the Foreign Minister, the Defense Agency and
the U.S. military regarding the unusually short notice of the
drills given by the Americans. They also complained that the
exercise were being carried out over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the mayors of Hino and Hachioji, western Tokyo, the
Kanagawa prefectural government and seven cities near the
U.S. base also urged the U.S. military to stop the drills.
</P>
<P>
The drills, conducted by aircraft attached to the U.S. aircraft
carrier "Independence," are scheduled to continue through Tuesday
at the Yokota and Iwakuni bases and through Wednesday at the
Atsugi base. 
</P>
</TEXT>
