<HEADLINE> Donations For China's Quake Area Coming In From Around Country </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- After an earthquake hit
Zhangjiakou in north China's Hebei Province on Saturday, people
from all over the country began making donations to help the
victims.
</P>
<P>
By Monday morning, army headquarters had sent over 30
truck-loads of goods worth more than four million yuan to the
quake site, and 600 tents that can house nearly 10,000 people.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Civil Affairs has sent 400 tents as well,
20,000 cotton-padded quilts, and five million yuan in relief funds.
</P>
<P>
The China Red Cross Society asked local branches to assist
people in the quake area, and has provided 100,000 yuan in relief
funds together with its Hebei branch.
</P>
<P>
The Red Cross Society of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region has donated one million yuan and Japan's Red Cross Society
has provided 10,000 blankets.
</P>
<P>
By 8:00 am (Beijing Time) Monday, the quake area had received
39,300 cotton-padded quilts, 580,000 items of cotton-padded
clothing, 20,000 coats, 500 woollen blankets, 1,100 tents, 85,000
kg of rice and flour, 8,470 cases of fast food, and 588 tons of
coal.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake, which measured 6.2 on the Richter Scale, hit an
area 200 km northwest of Beijing, at 11:50 am (Beijing Time) on
January 10, killing 47 people and injuring more than 2,000, and
destroying or damaging 70,000 houses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
