<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Welcomes Israeli Withdrawal Offer From </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Visiting French Foreign Minister
Hubert Vedrine Monday expressed welcome to Israel's offer to
withdraw from south Lebanon, but urged it to do so unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
According to local Voice of People radio, at a meeting with
Lebanese President Elias Hrawi, Vedrine said Israel's announced
readiness to accept the U.N. Security Council Resolution 425 is a
positive step in the right direction.
</P>
<P>
Israel's mentioning of the resolution, the first time since it
was adopted in 1978 calling for Israeli troop withdrawal from
Lebanon, should not be ignored, the French minister said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai last week proposed
that Israel accept the U.N. resolution and withdraw from the
security zone in south Lebanon, provided its northern security is
guaranteed by Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has rejected the offer, saying it cannot accept a
conditional withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out the 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in
south Lebanon in 1985 to protect its northern areas from attacks
by Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine reiterated France's support to Lebanon's just demand
that Israel comply with the Resolution 425 without conditions.
</P>
<P>
He said that as the Israelis add many conditions to the
implementation of the resolution, the offer can not be accepted by
Lebanon, and is unlikely to come true in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Besides the Resolution 425, the French minister also discussed
with Hrawi the whole situation in the Middle East, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine arrived here Sunday night on a regional tour which will
also take him to Jordan and Syria to further France's role in the
region and push forward the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
He has held talks with Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri,
House Speaker Nabih Berry and Foreign Minister Fares Boueiz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO: Fresh Fruits, Vegetables More Effective Against Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- People should make fresh fruits
and vegetables their first choice instead of plant constituents or
supplements such as carotenoids -- beta-carotene in particular --
to prevent cancer, according to a report released here Monday by
the World Health Organization (WHO).
</P>
<P>
Scientists of the WHO International Agency for Research on
Cancer (IARC) say that a new evaluation of all the published data
on the health effects of carotenoids has shown that beta-carotene,
in none of the clinical trials, has any significant preventive
effect in reducing the incidence and mortality rate of cancer.
</P>
<P>
"Our group came to the conclusion that, until further
information becomes available on how beta-carotene and other
carotenoids influence the process leading to cancer, none of these
substances should be promoted to the general population as a
tumor-preventive treatment," Dr. Harri Vainio, Chief of the
Chemoprevention Unit at IARC, said on behalf of a working group of
23 scientists from 10 countries.
</P>
<P>
"It appears at present that cancer prevention by fresh fruits
and vegetables remains more effective than taking one or several
of their constituents as dietary supplements," Dr Vainio
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan to Announce Appointment of Deputy Secretary-General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- UN Secretary-General
Kofi Annan will announce the appointment of deputy
secretary-general at today's noon briefing, the UN spoksman's
office said here today.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief recommended establishment of the post of deputy
secretary-general in his UN reform plan which was unveiled in
mid-July 1997. The 52nd session of the General Assembly of the
United Nations adopted a resolution and approved the establishment
on December 19, 1997.
</P>
<P>
According to the resolution, the post of deputy
secretary-general is an integral part of the Office of the
Secretary-General. The deputy will be appointed by the
secretary-general, with a term of office not exceeding his own,
and will assist the secretary-general in managing the operations
of the Secretariat, ensuring coherence of activities and
programs, and elevating "the profile and leadership of the United
Nations in the economic and social sphere." 
</P>
</TEXT>
