<P>
The rejection was announced Monday by Lee Jong-chan, chairman
of the takeover team, at a meeting of the forthcoming ruling National
Congress for New Politics (NCNP).
</P>
<P>
The team has asked the KHRCA not to place further orders for
the construction of a railway between Taejon and Taegu, the
second-phase of the controversial money-devouring Seoul-Pusan
high-speed railway project. The project has tripled its originally
estimated cost, reaching 17.6 trillion won ( about 1.1 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Currently, about 16 percent of the planned Seoul-Pusan railway
has been built.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the nation's large state-financed projects are
likely to be suspended or delayed in an effort to meet the harsh
loan conditions imposed by the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
They say many government projects will face drastic budget
reductions.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has suffered serious financial losses as a result
of conglomerate failures and bad loans by financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed with the IMF, South Korea has to open
its financial market, and budget and restructure its economy in
order to obtain a rescue loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
