<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia, IMF Share Same Views on Economic Reforms: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
has assured Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto that
Indonesia and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) share the same
views on how to carry out economic and financial reforms to save
the ailing Indonesian economy.
</P>
<P>
If any, their difference only lies in the timing of the
implementation of the reforms, Minister/State Secretary Moerdiono
said here Monday when briefing reporters on the phone conversation
between Soeharto and Hashimoto at 14:00 local time Monday.
</P>
<P>
Moerdiono said the IMF has assisted Indonesia in drawing up the
economic and financial reforms it will carry out, some of which
were disclosed by President Soeharto when he delivered the
proposed state budget for 1998-99 on January 6.
</P>
<P>
During the 35-minute phone conversation, Soeharto told
Hashimoto that Indonesia will seriously and wholeheartedly
implement the reforms which the IMF has agreed to.
</P>
<P>
He said the Indonesian and the IMF teams will work hard to
finish discussing all matters so that the talks between President
Soeharto and IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus will satisfy
both sides on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
IMF Deputy Managing Director Stanley Fischer is visiting in
Indonesia and had held talks with senior officials here. Camdesus
will arrive here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Moerdiono said, German Chancellor Helmut Kohl also
spoke to President Soeharto Monday by telephone, expressing his
confidence in Indonesia's capacity to overcome its monetary
crisis.
</P>
<P>
The phone conversations between Soeharto and leaders of foreign
countries as well as IMF officials visit was triggered by the
sudden fall of the Indonesian rupiah, which declined to a historic
low of 11,000 rupiah per dollar last Thursday. The rupiah has lost
more than 200 percent of its value since July last year.
</P>
<P>
At the end of October last year, IMF agreed to provide
Indonesia with financial and technical loans of 23 billion U.S.
dollars to help overcome its crisis and Indonesia made a
commitment to conduct economic and financial reforms.
</P>
<P>
However, the IMF was reportedly dissatisfied over the process
of the reforms in Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
