<HEADLINE> France Denies Violating Arms Embargo Against Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, January 12 (Xinhua) -- France denied violating an
international arms embargo Monday against Rwanda in May 1994.
</P>
<P>
According to a report in the French daily Le Figaro, the French
government under President Francois Mitterrand authorized the sale
of arms to Rwanda on May 17, 1994, one month after the then
Hutus-controlled army started a genocide against the Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
At least half a million Tutsis and moderate Hutus were killed
from April to July in 1994.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokesman Yves Doutriaux argued that
France stopped selling arms to Rwanda even before the
U.N. Security Council imposed in mid-May 1994 an arms embargo
against Rwanda, a decision which he said was made at the proposal
of France.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro said, however, that France continued to cooperate
with the Hutu government until the end of May 1994 -- if not later
-- 15 days after the United Nations imposed the arms embargo.
</P>
<P>
The daily also quoted a well-informed source as saying that
Mitterrand told one of his entourage in the summer of 1994: "In
these countries, a genocide is not too much." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
