<HEADLINE> South Korea's Auto Exports Up 8.2 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, January 12 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's auto export grew
8.2 percent to 1,319,685 units in 1997, some 110,000 units more
than in 1996, said the Korea Automobile Manufacturers Association
(KAMA) Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, the total number of the nation's car sales edged down
0.7 percent to 2,832,758 units in 1997, about 21,500 units less
than in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The country also suffered a drop of 2.5 percent in domestic
sales, which fell to 1,513,073 units in the same year, some 42,500
units less than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Hyundai Motor Co. topped the 1997 list of car exports with
565,295 units, followed by Daewoo Motor Co. and Kia Motors
Corp. with 334,802 and 281,523 units.
</P>
<P>
In domestic sales, Hyundai also ranked first with 645,615 units
last year, followed by Kia and Daewoo with 293,592 and 354,210
units.
</P>
<P>
The Sonata III, a mid-size sedan by Hyundai, was the
best-selling car in the country last year, with sales hitting
158,396 units. 
</P>
