<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January (Xinhua) -- Visiting British Prime Minister Tony
Blair and his Japanese counterpart Ryutaro Hashimoto agreed Monday
on Setting a common vision for the 21st century that calls for
enhancing Asia-Europe ties and creation of a better global
community.
</P>
<P>
In a summit meeting, the two leaders also agreed to cooperate
so as to cope with the current economic turmoil in Asian
economies, Japanese Foreign Ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
As a manifestation of enhancing Asia-Europe relations, Blair
and Hashimoto stressed the importance of the Asia-Europe
Meeting (ASEM) whose second summit talks will be held in London in
April.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders noted that they would make further efforts for
bringing to success the ASEM summit and the annual summit of the
Group of Seven industrialized nations and Russia in Birmingham in
May, over both of which Blair will preside.
</P>
<P>
As their common vision for the 21st century, the two leaders
also picked reform and investment for the future through expansion
of cultural exchanges between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
In order to create a better global economy, the two leaders
agreed that they would take leads for tackling global issues such
as proliferation of weapons of mass destruction, terrorism and
combating poverty.
</P>
<P>
Blair arrived here last Friday for a five-day visit to
Japan. 
</P>
