<HEADLINE> Johansson: England Could Cost Europe 2006 World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- UEFA President Lennart Johansson
said on Monday that England's decision to compete with Germany for
the right to host the 2006 World Cup could cost Europe the chance
of winning the bid.
</P>
<P>
The 68-year-old Johansson, who is hoping to succeed Joao
Havelange as head of FIFA in June, also told the English daily
newspaper "The Independent" that there was no future for a
European Super League.
</P>
<P>
The Swede, who was responsible for persuading UEFA in allowing
English clubs back into European competition after the 1985 Heysel
stadium tragedy and lobbied successfully for England hosting
Euro '96, said that England and Germany had started their
campaigns too early.
</P>
<P>
"What worries me in particular is the early start that both
countries have made," Johansson said.
</P>
<P>
"They must remember that other parts of the world such as
Africa and Brazil could entertain hopes of hosting the
tournament. Both Germany and England should have waited before
spending the money they already have. It could be a big waste of
money and time," he added.
</P>
<P>
Johansson, who says he will retire and go fishing if he does
not claim the FIFA presidency, said that players needed more time
off and a European Super League was not on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
Johansson also said in the paper that the ticketing
arrangements for this year's World Cup could have been handled
better.
</P>
<P>
"If I were the president I would change the system. Too small a
number of tickets is being given to outsiders," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Norway for example had hopes of 50,000 tickets but received
just 3,000. There is always criticism over this at every World
Cup, but this time it is particularly low, and it is too late to
do anything about it," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
