<HEADLINE> Finland, Philippines to Strengthen Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Finland and the Philippines have
agreed to strengthen their bilateral relations and economic
cooperation, especially in trade and investment areas.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during the 30-minute meeting between
Finnish Minister of European Affairs Ole Norrback and Philippine
President Fidel Ramos on Monday.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Norrback reaffirmed his country's continued
confidence in the economic potentials of the Philippines despite
the ongoing financial turmoil in Asia.
</P>
<P>
He told Ramos that Finland wants to expand the areas of
economic cooperation with the Philippines in the midst of economic
difficulty in Southeast Asia "because we want to help and try to
stabilize the situation."
</P>
<P>
Ramos told Norrback that the sustained economic growth now
enjoyed by the Philippines is a result of the "bitter pills we
swallowed six years ago."
</P>
<P>
"Now, we are cured of our illness at a time when our neighbors
are entering the hospital for treatment," he said, referring to
the bailout package other Asian countries sought from the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine president and the Finnish minister agreed there
is a need to create more markets for Philippine-made products in
Finland to bridge the trade gap which has always been in favor of
Finland.
</P>
<P>
Total trade in 1996 between the two countries amounted to 118.4
million US dollars, with a trade deficit for the Philippines
registered at 64 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the trade deficit for the Philippines increased
further to 69.6 million dollars, with Philippine exports
registered at 16.37 million dollars and imports valued at 85.94
million dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
