<HEADLINE> Britain Needs More Flexibility In Trade: Wu Yi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Trade Minister
Wu Yi said at the second meeting of the Sino-British Economic and
Trade Cooperation Committee today that Britain should be more
flexible in trade with China, especially in technology transfers.
</P>
<P>
Wu, minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation, chaired
the meeting together with British Minister of Trade and Industry
Magaret Beckett, who is the first cabinet minister of the new
British government to visit China.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that bilateral economic and trade co-operation has been
fairly sound since the committee's first meeting in 1996.
Bilateral trade exceeded five billion US dollars in 1996, making
Britain China's third largest trading partner in the EU, she said.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Britain became China's second largest trading partner
in the EU, with bilateral trade in the first eleven months of 1997
exceeding five billion US dollars, up 16.2 percent over the same
period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Britain is also EU's largest investor in China. By the end of
September 1997, Britain had invested in 2,018 projects in China,
with more than 13 billion US dollars in funding, 4.48 billion
dollars of which has been put to use.
</P>
<P>
But, despite the progress, the situation still does not fit
Britain's position as a trader and investor in the world economy,
Wu said, and that the two countries' economies complement each
other and that economic and trade co-operation has great potential.
</P>
<P>
She expressed the hope that both sides will use the committee
for closer contacts between government departments and will
increase cooperation through symposiums, business fairs and
personnel exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Beckett said she agreed that the two sides should have a
strategic view of bilateral economic and trade relations and deal
with problems with a long-term perspective.
</P>
<P>
The British are well aware of the fact that there is great
potential to be tapped and that Britain is willing to establish
long-term economic and trade ties with China and to increase
cooperation with China in transportation, telecommunications, food
processing, and other areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
