<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwandan Army Kills 18 Rebel Militiamen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan army killed 18
Hutu rebel militiamen in clashes in the northwest over the
weekend, military sources have indicated.
</P>
<P>
"They attacked Nyamyumba commune Saturday night, trying to
burn its offices," the army spokesman, Major Emmanuel Ndahiro
told Rwanda News Agency (RNA) today.
</P>
<P>
Ndahiro said that the army intervened and extinguished the
fire, killing 18 assailants and seizing four rifles, and four of
the rebels were injured, a RNA report said.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan army is still pursuing the Hutu armed insurgents
who have been involved in various criminal acts in the area like
ambushing vehicles and killing passengers, as well as
slaughtering local leaders.
</P>
<P>
Military sources in Gisenyi have reported that since December
31, 1997 to January 9, 1998, the rebel militiamen ambushed nine
vehicles on Nyundo-Gisenyi road, and killed 30 people.
</P>
<P>
"There are elements who are supportive of the militiamen in
that part of Gisenyi," Ndahiro said.
</P>
<P>
That area where insecurity has heightened for the past days
includes the communes of Nyamyumba, Kanama, and Rubavu.
</P>
<P>
Hutu rebels in Rwanda, Burundi and the east of Democratic
Congo or former Zaire, increasingly coordinate strategy in
cross-border attacks, regional analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni went to Rwanda at the
weekend to discuss the upsurge of rebel activity in the three
countries with Rwandan leaders, African diplomats here said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
