<HEADLINE> Israeli Parliament Speaker Works to Prevent Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Knesset (parliament)
Speaker Dan Tichon today held a meeting with Gesher (bridge)
Party leader David Levy to prevent a possible fall of the
government, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held hours before the Knesset's voting on the
no-confidence motions against Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The Knesset is scheduled to vote Monday afternoon on the two
no-confidence motions tabled by the opposition Labor and Meretz
parties over the state budget passed in the Knesset a week ago.
</P>
<P>
The opposition parties said that some agreements reached by
the prime minister and other coalition parties on certain 1998
budget allocations are against the legal regulations. They tabled
the no-confidence motions shortly after the budget's approval.
</P>
<P>
Levy and his other four Gesher Knesset members voted against
the budget. The coalition now only has 61 seats in the 120-member
Knesset after Levy's resignation as foreign minister on January 4
and the departure of the other four Gesher Knesset members.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, an absolute majority of 61 lawmakers is enough
to topple the ruling coalition.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that if the Gesher joins the opposition in
voting for the no-confidence motions, the government will
certainly be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
Tichon was quoted as saying that the Gesher is still a part of
the ruling Likud coalition although Levy resigned, and the
government has already reached an agreement for fund allocations
with the Gesher party in the 1998 budget.
</P>
<P>
With this agreement still being effective, Tichon said, he has
to work out with Levy to ensure that Gesher will not vote against
the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Levy said he will consult his Gesher members on this matter
before making final decisions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
