<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Not to Buy New Defense Equipment due to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia said Monday that
there would be no new purchase of defense equipment for its armed
forces because of the country's economic downturn and the
depreciation of its currency -- the ringgit.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Defense Minister Syed Hamid Albar conveyed the
message to U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen who wanted to know
Malaysia's policy on the matter, according to the Malaysian
national news agency Bernama.
</P>
<P>
Any expenses would be for the maintenance and servicing of
existing defense equipment, Syed Hamid said after meeting Cohen
who arrived here Sunday for a three-day visit to Malaysia as part
of his tour to several Asian countries, Bernama said.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid said the two sides also discussed bilateral issues
and the United States in particular wanted to know Malaysia's
stand on several issues especially defense and security under the
presence condition.
</P>
<P>
"Apart from discussing intelligence cooperation and efforts to
enhance ties in defense science, I told him (Cohen) that all
defense planning would continue," Syed Hamid was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid said Cohen, who wanted to know whether Malaysia
would continue to send military officers for training in the
United States under the International Military Education and
Training (IMET) and Bilateral Training Consultancy Group, was told
that Malaysia would continue sending the office for training in
selected fields since all expenses would be borne by the United
States.
</P>
<P>
He said that Cohen was also told that Malaysia was satisfied
with earlier discussion resulting in a five-year contract to
maintain and service U.S. Air Force Hercules C-130 aircraft at
Malaysia's Airod.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid also told Cohen of Malaysia's commitment to send its
troops to serve with Stabilization Force together with other
troops from NATO and the United States in Bosnia-Herzegovina after
the mandate expired in June, according to Bernama.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid said "For the moment, the government's decision is
to continue to deploy its troops pending the outcome of
discussions in March."
</P>
<P>
The discussion is to commit the continued participation for
NATO and U.S. forces in Bosnia and so far Malaysia has agreed to
continue its commitment in that country, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
