<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hashimoto Vows to Revitalize Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto said Monday he will do his best to stabilize Japan's
financial system and stimulate the flagging economy.
</P>
<P>
In a speech delivered at the opening of the 150-day regular
Diet (parliament) session, Hashimoto said, "I will make every
effort to prevent Japan from sparking a financial and economic
panic, to stabilize the financial system, which is the nation's
economic artery, and to regain the confidence of investors in the
future of the economy."
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto said a stable financial system and an economic
recovery are needed to carry out his pledged reforms.
</P>
<P>
He asked opposition parties to cooperate and pass a
supplementary budget and related bills as soon as possible for
fiscal 1997, and to pave the way for a two trillion yen (about
15.2 billion U.S. dollars) income tax cut.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto detailed measures to stablize the financial system,
featuring a 30 trillion yen (about 227.3 billion dollars) outlay
of public money to protect depositors and the overall system,
as well as establishing a 25 trillion yen (about 189.4
billion dollars) line of credit in public funds to ease the credit
crunch faced by small and medium-sized companies.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said he expects the financial system
stabilization measures and other economic stimulus plans will help
realize an economic rebound.
</P>
<P>
The convening of the regular Diet session, originally planned
for January 19, was moved up a week so lawmakers could address the
country's sluggish economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
