<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Flying Start For China in Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 12 (Xinhua) -- China jumped to a flying start as
Chen Yan proved she was undisputed No.1 and Zeng Qiliang broke the
Chinese drought of men's swimming medal at the world swimming
championships on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Chen, world record holder, won China's first
swimming title here as she touched the pad in 4:36.66 at the
women's 400m individual medley.
</P>
<P>
Zeng got China's first ever world championship medal in the
men's events, finishing only second to Belgium's Olympic champion
Frederik Deburghgraeve at the 100m butterfly.
</P>
<P>
Chen could hardly conceal her excitement after the race.
</P>
<P>
"We have had hard times since we arrived in Perth, " she
said. "Our training has often been interrupted by media and we
have many other distractions."
</P>
<P>
"The victory is a morale-booster to me, as well as to the
Chinese team. I'm very, very excited right now," she said.
</P>
<P>
Yana Klochkova of Ukraine picked the silver medal in 4:45.94
and Japanese Yasuko Tajima got the bronze in 4:39.45.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Wu Yanyan, who led the field until the last turn,
looked worn out in the final stretch, missing the podium by 0.74
seconds.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't see Wu Yanyan until with 100 meters to go," Chen
said. "I had thought I was leading all the way."
</P>
<P>
Deburghgraeve, who holds the world record of 1:00.60 in the
men's 100m breastroke, snatched his speciality event in 1:01:34,
just 0.42 adrift of Zeng.
</P>
<P>
Zeng, who stands just 1.72 meters, called himself as a "giant".
</P>
<P>
"I am a giant," he said. "In my eyes, only Deburghgraeve stands
taller than me."
</P>
<P>
Zeng was born into a fisherman's family in South China's
Guangdong province and he started swimming since he learned to
walk.
</P>
<P>
"I was brought up in the Zhujiang river in Guangdong," he said.
</P>
<P>
American veteran Jenny Thompson won the women's 100m freestyle
and Australian Michael Klim triumphed in the men's 200m freestyle.
</P>
<P>
Thompson, Pan Pacific champion, came first in 54.95 seconds,
beating second-place finisher Martina Moravcova by 0.14 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Shan Ying, world No. 2 in the event, got the bronze
medal in 55.10.
</P>
<P>
Klim, world No.1 in both the 100m butterfly and 200m freestyle
events, clocked 1:47.41 to win the 200m freestyle final.
</P>
<P>
The Australian star was followed by Italian Massi Rosolino and
Dutchman Hoogenband van Den.
</P>
<P>
Early in the day, the Chinese duo Xu Hao and Yu Zhuocheng edged
Americans Troy Dumais and Holger Schlepps to win the 3m
synchronized diving title.
</P>
<P>
It was the second gold medal for the 22-year-old Yu, who won
the 1m springboard title last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In the women's platform contention, Ukrainian two-time Olympian
Olena Zhupyna faced little challenge on her way to the top.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Cai Yuyan and Chen Li, both 15, got the silver and
bronze medal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
