<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 9.5 Percent Growth In Beijing's GDP In 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital's GDP for
1997 was 180 billion yuan, a growth of 9.5 percent, the Municipal
Statistics Bureau announced today.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing New Technological and Industrial Development Zone
had a GDP of 13 billion, up 25 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The retail price index and consumer price index both dropped
below the growth rate and the gap in supply and demand went from
nine percent in 1995 to five percent.
</P>
<P>
Last year Beijing had 95 billion yuan in capital investment,
but the real estate market remained sluggish, with market sales
dropping by 15 percent and some 1.2 million square meters of
residential and office buildings remaining unoccupied.
</P>
<P>
The city utilized 2.5 billion US dollars in foreign funds
last year, with capital assests of joint venture projects approved
amounting to twice what they were a year before.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the city's revenues increased 25 percent and the
average wages for workers were 11,000 yuan, up nine percent from
1996.
</P>
<P>
Beijing had some 2.3 million overseas tourists last year,
generating 2.25 billion US dollars in hard currency earnings, but
the hotel occupancy rate remained as low as 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Zou Chunlan, vice director of the Beijing Statistics Bureau
says that, with 70,000 workers laid off, the city government is
under some pressure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine United Opposition Chairman Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Senate President
Ernesto Maceda on Monday formally tendered his resignation as
chairman of the country's united opposition the Struggle of
Patriotic Filipino Masses, pushing the party on the brink of a
breakup.
</P>
<P>
But Maceda's resignation letter did not categorically stated
whether he is taking with him the entire Nationalist People's
Coalition (NPC) on his way out of the united opposition, known as
LAMMP in Filipino.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here said Maceda, president of the NPC,
maybe is not a real leader of the coalition, and the NPC's
withdrawal from the mainstream opposition need the blessing of NPC
chairman, business tycoon Eduardo Cojuangco.
</P>
<P>
Maceda has threatened to break away from the LAMMP since late
last year, especially after losing to Senator Edgardo Angara in
the race for the LAMMP's vice presidential candidacy last month.
</P>
<P>
In December 1997, Angara agreed to abandon his presidential bid
and run as the running mate of Vice President Joseph Estrada, who
has enjoyed high approval ratings in many opinion surveys, in the
May presidential polls to prevent a breakup of the LAMMP.
</P>
<P>
The LAMMP, created in June 1997, consists of the NPC led by
Maceda, the Patriotic Filipino Masses party led by Estrada and the
then biggest opposition the Struggle of Democratic Filipinos led
by Angara.
</P>
<P>
But Maceda, a main broker of the united opposition, has
repeatedly indicated his intention to leave the united opposition
in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said Maceda has been negotiating with the
ruling Lakas-NUCD party on a merger of the NPC and the Lakas led
by President Fidel Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Maceda is now reportedly on his way to Australia to meet with
Cojuangco and seek the latter's approval for his move to withdraw
the party from the LAMMP.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
