<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Seismologists Go To Study Quake Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHANGBEI, HEBEI PROVINCE, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese
seismologists are gathering data and monitoring aftershocks of the
strong earthquake that jolted Shangyi and Zhangbei counties in
Hebei Province at noon on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake's epicenter was 220 kilometers northwest of
Beijing. It left 47 people dead and over 9,000 injured, and more
than 70,000 houses in 13 townships destroyed or seriously damaged.
</P>
<P>
A group headed by the deputy director of the State Seismology
Bureau, Ge Zhizhou, arrived at the site five hours after the
earthquake, braving sub-zero temperatures to do a field study.
</P>
<P>
Ge said the earthquake hit what had been designated as a
high-risk area by seismologists two years ago in northwest Beijing
and neighboring parts of Shanxi and Hebei provinces, and Inner
Mongolia. The chances are slim that the Zhangbei-Shangyi region
will be hit by powerful earthquakes, he said, but the Hebei
Provincial Seismology Bureau has set up a temporary station in
Zhangjiakou to monitor developments.
</P>
<P>
Experts point out that a general lack of knowledge about
earthquake prevention by local people is partly to blame for the
heavy losses, and that the houses damaged were poorly
made. 
</P>
</TEXT>
