<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Sue US on F-16 Planes Issue: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Pakistani government
confirmed Monday that it is preparing to file a suit against the
U.S. administration on the issue of stuck-up F-16 fighters and a
legal firm has been hired to study the case.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question at the weekly press briefing, a
Foreign Office spokesman said that while the Pakistani government
was in contact with the U.S. administration on the issues, it has
been consistently demanding supply of the planes or return of the
money it has paid for them.
</P>
<P>
"This has been our unchanging position," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Gohar Ayub Khan told the local English daily
"The Nation" last Thursday that Pakistan would go to American
courts in the next few weeks to get back 656 million US dollars it
had paid for the stuck-up F-16 fighters.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said all paper and legal work for filing a
suit against the U.S. administration has been prepared by
Pakistan's legal experts.
</P>
<P>
The delivery of 28 F-16s was stopped by the U.S. administration
after the enforcement of Pressler Amendment in the early 90s. The
Pressler Amendment had restrained the U.S. administration from
providing military hardware to Pakistan on the basis of its
alleged nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
However, after the passage of Brown Amendment, the U.S.
administration made an abortive attempt to sell the stuck-up F-16s
to a third country and give the proceeds of the sale to Pakistan.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
