<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Industries Draft Measures to Stop Peso </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Local industries have drafted
three-point action program to stop speculation on the peso against
the US dollar and cushion the impact of the emerging economic
crisis, the Philippine News Agency reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Raul Concepcion, president of the Federation
of Philippine Industries, as saying that he will discuss the
program with President Fidel Ramos, the Central Bank Governor
Gabriel Singson and the Bankers Association of the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Concepcion said the first measure is that exporters will be
temporarily compelled to surrender their export proceeds to banks
in return for a guarantee.
</P>
<P>
The guarantee can be bought back at the same rate, a percentage
of these proceeds to be used to finance their importation.
</P>
<P>
He said the central bank will also issue a 90-day bills to
those who surrender their dollars, except the exporters.
</P>
<P>
To encourage dollar owners to shift to pesos, these bills will
carry interest yield of 10 percentage points above the 90-day
treasury bill which is currently at 19 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, to importation of non-essential and semi-essential
consumer goods to a temporary time deposit of 180 days and 120
days, respectively, tariff equivalent to the value of the
importation will be imposed.
</P>
<P>
Concepcion noted that there is lack of urgency in dealing with
the crisis because of concern that any measures, even if
temporary, to curb imports and dampen currency speculations, will
violate the country's commitments under the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) and the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, he pointed out, the IMF and WTO should
appreciate the above pro-active measures as preventive steps
against balance of payments difficulties and subsequent return to
the IMF for a bailout.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine peso has depreciated against the dollar for
around 70 percent since the financial crisis hit the country last
July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
