<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Resistance Prompts Israeli Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese House Speaker Nabih
Berry today said that the recent Israeli withdrawal offer should
be attributed to Lebanese guerrillas resistance against its
occupation, a local radio reported.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at a meeting with the visiting French
Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine who is on a Middle East tour, the
Voice of the People reported.
</P>
<P>
Berry stressed that if Israelis really intend to comply with
the U.N. Security Council resolution 425 and withdraw its troops
from south Lebanon, it is certainly a good thing and is resulted
from the Lebanese people's struggle, especially the residents in
the south.
</P>
<P>
Since 1985 when Israel carved out a 1,200-square-kilometer
area in south Lebanon as the buffer zone to protect its residents
in the north, Lebanese guerrillas have been fighting with its
troops.
</P>
<P>
Last year, a total of 39 Israeli soldiers were killed, 95
wounded, in battles with guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Berry pointed out that if the purpose of the Israeli withdrawal
offer aims at the division of Syrian and Lebanese track in the
peace talks with Israel, it is never acceptable. Israel has
suggested to give the Lebanese issue a priority.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai
announced that his country is ready to accept the resolution
425 provided arrangements are agreed to protect Israel's
security after the withdrawal of its troops from south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the speaker told the French minister that the peace
cannot be limited only to Israel, or any country in the region
and, it should be a comprehensive and lasting peace.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that Syrian and Lebanese track which has
been deadlocked since February 1996 should be given equal
attention as the Palestinian track in the peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine, who arrived here Sunday night, had held talks with
Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz on the regional situation and Israeli withdrawal offer.
</P>
<P>
He will leave Lebanon for Jordan and Syria later today on a
regional tour aimed at reviving the stalled peace process and
seeking a larger role in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
