<HEADLINE> Egypt's Parliament Urges Tough Arab Stance on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The People's Assembly in Egypt
today called on the upcoming emergency Arab parliamentary
conference to adopt a strong stance on fighting terrorism, the
Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The emergency session of the Arab Parliamentary Union (APU)
slated for Wednesday in the Upper Egyptian city of Luxor is
expected to come up with an initiative in confrontation of the
phenomenon of terrorism and in solidarity with Egypt's efforts in
this respect.
</P>
<P>
In a report to be submitted to the session, the Egyptian
parliament calls upon Arab states to hold consultations on means
of setting up an effective coordination system in fighting
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The People's Assembly underlined that terrorism is an
impediment to democracy and development, a matter that requires an
overall strategy at various levels to deal with.
</P>
<P>
It also warned that the phenomenon of terrorism threatens
Egypt's national resources and thwarts its chance in overall
development.
</P>
<P>
President Hosni Mubarak will give a keynote speech to the
meeting of the parliamentarians from 18 Arab countries who will
gather in Luxor to express their solidarity with Egypt following a
terrorist attack in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Luxor, the venue of the Arab emergency meeting, witnessed a
brutal massacre of 58 foreign tourists and four Egyptians by six
Islamic militants on November 17, 1997 in Egypt's worst militant
attack since 1992. Revenues from Egypt's vital tourism sector have
plummeted since then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
