<HEADLINE> Share Prices Decline Sharply on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Share prices declined sharply
on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials
Index (STII) lost 102.88 points to close at 1073.47 points on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that there was some short covering before the
close. But sentiment continued to remain very weak, they said,
predicting that the STII is set to fall below 1000 in the next few
days.
</P>
<P>
Selling of banks and property stocks was especially heavy due
to concerns over banks' exposure to the economic crisis in Asia
and over rising domestic interest rates, they noted.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume stood at 301.08 million units, valued
at 609.04 million Singapore dollars (340.25 million US dollars).
Declines overwhelmed advances by 357 to 30, while 225 other
counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Wing Tai was the most actively traded counter as it registered
a turnover of 23.66 million units. It was followed by Hong Kong
Land which had 20.8 million shares traded. DBS (Development Bank
of Singapore) Land was next with 18.36 million shares traded.
</P>
<P>
Clipsal led the gainers of the day as it rose by nine cents to
end at 1.19 US dollars. Courts increased by eight cents to close
at 33 Singapore cents. CMB Asia picked up by six cents to finish
at 68 Singapore cents.
</P>
<P>
City Development warrant98 was the biggest loser as it declined
by 3.44 dollars to close at 1.46 Singapore dollars. GuangZhou
Investment fell by 2.4 dollars to finish at 1.1 Hong Kong dollars.
The Singapore Press Holdings (SPH) lost 2.1 dollars to end at 12.5
Singapore dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
