<HEADLINE> CPPCC Proposals In Beijing Give Policy-makers Ideas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Proposals from members of the
Beijing Municipal Committee of the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference (CPPCC) have become an important source of
ideas for local policy-makers, according to Zhu Zupu, deputy
secretary-general of the Beijing Municipal Government.
</P>
<P>
Zhu told a press conference here today that, over the past five
years, local CPPCC members, non-communist party members, and
non-governmental organizations made 5,003 proposals, 60 percent of
which were adopted.
</P>
<P>
The Municipal Communist Party Committee and Municipal
Government had a proposal for information infrastructure in
September of 1996 and it was put into effect that year.
</P>
<P>
A 360-sq.m. museum built on top of some old ruins on Wangfujing
Street in downtown Beijing was the result of a proposal on
protecting cultural relics, Zhu added. Other proposals have helped
local government offices settle traffic, power supply, and living
standard problems.
</P>
<P>
It is important for the Party and government departments to
continue to improve the multi-party cooperation and political
consultation under the leadership of the CPC in this way, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
