<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Committed to Asian Economies' Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States Monday
reiterated its commitment to help revitalize the Asian economies
badly hit by the currency and stock market crises.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. commitment was conveyed by its Defense Secretary
William Cohen to Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad during
their 40-minute meeting here, Malaysian Foreign Ministry
Under-Secretary for Southeast Asia and South Pacific Mohamed
Arshad M. Hussain told reporters at a news briefing after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said that Cohen informed Mahathir that U.S. President Bill
Clinton was constantly getting the views of his advisers to ensure
that Washington played an important and effective role in tackling
the economic turmoil in the region.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Arshad said Cohen also informed Mahathir that the U.S.,
being one of the biggest investors in the region, took a serious
view of the problems faced by the Asian economies.
</P>
<P>
The official said that Mahathir welcomed U.S. leaders to visit
the region to see for themselves what was happening, and this was
because the western leaders, including those from the United
States, regarded the economic problems and position of all
countries of the region as similar when in fact each economy had
its own strengths and weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed Arshad said Mahathir also expressed his satisfaction
with the bilateral ties between Kuala Lumpur and Washington.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also touched on the presence of U.S. troops in
the region and Mahathir said the present U.S. strength was
sufficient, Mohamed Arshad told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Cohen, who arrived here on Sunday, is on a three-day visit to
Malaysia, the first leg of his 12-day tour to several Asian
countries, and he attended the two-day Fourth Pacific Dialogue
opened by Mahathir on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
