<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Introduce New National Agriculture Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Malaysian government
will introduce a new National Agriculture Policy (NAP),
emphasising commercial food production by the private sector, its
Deputy Agriculture Minister Tengku Mahmud Mansor said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The new policy would promote large-scale production of food not
only to cut the country's food imports but also to boost food
exports, he said in Teluk Intan, about 165 kilometers northwest
from here, according to an official media report.
</P>
<P>
The new NAP would be presented to the cabinet in two to three
months time, Tengku Mahmud said.
</P>
<P>
Under the policy, he said, oil palm estate owners would be
encouraged to rear cattle on a scale which exceeded domestic
demand so that they could serve the export market.
</P>
<P>
Tengku Mahmud said although the country was already producing
more than enough chickens and eggs for domestic consumption, the
new policy would promote improved production for exports.
</P>
<P>
The new policy would also encourage deep-fish fishing as a
means to boost the fisheries sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia spends about 10 billion ringgit (about 2.2 billion
U.S. dollars) annually on food imports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Not Experiencing Retrenchment of Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia has not
experienced retrenchment of workers in big numbers despite the
current economic problem, instead it is still facing shortage of
workers, its Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Anwar's statement was made at a time when there are talks in
the air about the retrenchment of workers by enterprises due to
the slowdown in economic activities following the current currency
and stock market turmoil affecting the country.
</P>
<P>
"There is still full employment," he told reports at a news
conference here.
</P>
<P>
There is an immediate need for 60,000 workers in the plantation
sector and 20,000 workers in the manufacturing sector, said Anwar,
who is also Finance Minister.
</P>
<P>
Anwar, who is also chairman of the cabinet committee on foreign
workers, said foreign workers whose permits have not expired but
had their services terminated would be re-deployed into these
sectors.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has employed about two million foreign workers mainly
from Indonesia, Bangladesh, the Philippines and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said only foreign workers who are needed in priority
areas would be retained.
</P>
<P>
"Those illegal workers will have to go home," he said, hoping
the governments of countries whose citizens have been repatriated
would understand Malaysia's move.  
</P>
</TEXT>
