<HEADLINE> Good Scientific Cooperation Between Guangzhou, Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Lin Shusen, the mayor of
Guangzhou in southern China, said today that his city and Hong
Kong have gotten along well for the past two decades in
manufacturing and that scientific and technological cooperation
look promising in the future.
</P>
<P>
This was made possible by inexpensive labor and plentiful land
resources in Guangzhou and nearby areas, Lin told reporters at the
first session of the Ninth Guangdong Provincial People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Land prices have gotten higher, however, and labor is no longer
as cheap as it was, but Hong Kong manufacturers haven't moved away
because business people want to improve the technological edge of
their enterprises, Lin said.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou has most of the institutions of higher learning and
80 percent of the research institutes in Guangdong Province, and
Hong Kong, for its part, has ties to the international market.
</P>
<P>
In this way, the mayor said, the two have many fine advantages
in scientific and technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
A month ago, Lin headed a science delegation in a visit to Hong
Kong and made contacts with people in business and science and
technology for future cooperation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
