<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Shares Close Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks fell by 8.69
percent on Monday, in reaction to the recent continuous fall of
Asian markets and the news that influential Hong Kong-based
Peregrine Investment Holdings Ltd. was heading for liquidation.
</P>
<P>
The company gave up efforts for survival and an application was
lodged for liquidation, a company spokesman announced Monday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Some company staff had already taken personal belongings out of
the offices before the announcement was made after the stock
market closed on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The key Hang Seng Index, which traces the performance of 33
blue chips listed on the Hong Kong Exchange, lost 773.58 points to
close at 8,121.06.
</P>
<P>
The index once hit a low of 7,909.13 points, its lowest level
since March 1995.
</P>
<P>
The turnover amounted to 13,332 million HK dollars (1,709
million US dollars), against 11,650 HK dollars (1,493 million US
dollars) last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Index lost 680.32 points, or 7.64 percent, to open at
8,214.32 and fell 985.51 points to close at 7,909.13 at midday.
</P>
<P>
The shares lost 359.89 points, or 3.89 percent, to close at
8,894.64 last Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
