<HEADLINE> Tanzania Cellular Phone Firm to Expand Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's cellular
telephone company Mobitel plans to invest 17 million U.S. Dollars
in expanding its services in 1998, according to a report by The
Guardian today.
</P>
<P>
"Mobitel is ready for major expansion this year," the paper
said, citing a statement released by the company.
</P>
<P>
By May, the company will be expanding services in Moshi,
Shinyanga, Tanga, Dodoma and Mbeya regions. And by the end of
this year, the company expects to provide services in Pemba,
Mtwara, Songea and Tabora, which will be convenient for customers
to use their mobile phones in more places.
</P>
<P>
"Mobitel share-holders are fully supportive of the expansion
and believe the recent government policy is creating a more
attractive environment for investors." it said.
</P>
<P>
The Mobitel share-holders are Millicom International Cellular,
The Tanzania Telecommunications Company Limited and the Ultimate
Security.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Mobitel invested 15 million U.S. Dollars in expanding
services, including the opening of five radio stations in Dar es
Salaam and Zanzibar.
</P>
<P>
Last June, the first Mobitel service was opened in Arusha and
Mwanza regions, allowing customers to roam between Dar es Salaam,
Arusha, Zanzibar and Mwanza with their hand-sets.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that radio boosters installed last December
in Arusha and Mwanza will be operational this month. 
</P>
