<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Faces Serious Budget Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran is facing a serious budget
deficit of 4.57 billion U.S. dollars in the current Iranian fiscal
year (ending on March 20) due to the oil price fall in the
international market, a senior Iranian official has announced.
</P>
<P>
Vice President and Head of the Plan and Budget Organization
Mohammad Ali Najafi Sunday urged the country's Majlis (parliament)
to take immediate measures to deal with the budget deficit of
8 trillion rials (about 4.57 billion dollars), local daily
Tehran Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
Parts of the revenues stipulated in the budget have not
materialized, leading to the deficit in the current fiscal year,
Najafi said at the open session of the Majlis. He called for an
amendment to the budget.
</P>
<P>
The Majlis Sunday approved a bill amending the balanced budget
with a projection of state income at 75.1 trillion rials (about
42.86 billion dollars), but no details of the amendment were
revealed, the daily said.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian government of former President Hashemi Rafsanjani
expected 17.7 billion dollars from oil revenue during the current
Iranian year based on an average price of 17.5 dollars per barrel
for Iranian crude oil.
</P>
<P>
However, prices for Iranian crude oil dropped to 15-16 dollars
and the country only fetched 10 billion dollars in the first
eight months of the current Iranian year. Experts said that the
annual revenue from oil exports for the country would be around
15 billion dollars with the current oil price, some 15.5 percent
below the projection figure.
</P>
<P>
Iran's oil production was 3.6 million barrels per day (bpd) in
1997 with some 2.5 million bpd for export. The country's oil
production ceiling was raised to 3.94 million bpd according to a
decision by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC) last November.
</P>
<P>
Many parliament members have urged for a realistic projection
for the country's oil revenue in the new year budget. Debates on
details of the new budget began today after the parliament
approved its outlines Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The government of President Mohammad Khatami anticipated an
earning of 14.9 billion dollars from oil exports based on an
average price of 17.5 dollars in its first balanced budget, but
most of the parliament members believed it was impossible for the
government to achieve the target.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that the Majlis would cut down the
country's expenditures for the new year since it was pessimistic
on the country's oil revenue in the new year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
