<HEADLINE> Chen Wins China's First Swimming Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 12 (Xinhua) -- China's world record holder Chen
Yan touched home first to lift the women's 400m individual medley
title at the world swimming championships here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Chen clocked four minutes and 36.66 seconds,
nearly two seconds outside of her world mark of 4:34.79 set in the
Chinese National Games last year.
</P>
<P>
Chen said after the race that she could hardly describe her
excitement.
</P>
<P>
"We have had hard times since we arrived in Perth, " she
said. "Our training has often been interrupted by media and we
have many other distractions."
</P>
<P>
"The victory is a morale-booster to me, as well as to the
Chinese team. I'm very, very excited right now," she said, her
voice trembling.
</P>
<P>
Yana Klochkova of Ukraine, who clocked 4:45.94, picked the
silver medal and Japanese Joanne Malar got the bronze in 4:39.45.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Wu Yanyan, who led the field until the last turn,
looked worn out in the final stretch, finishing only fourth in
4:40.16.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't see Wu Yanyan until with 100 meters to go," Chen
said. "I had thought I was leading all the way."
</P>
<P>
Chen Yan began swimming at the age of 6 and joined the Liaoning
club in Northeast China at 12.
</P>
<P>
Chen jumped into fame in October 1995 when she swept the 400m
individual medley, 200m and 400m freestyle events in the Chinese
City Games in Nanjing.
</P>
<P>
She reached the peak of her career in the Chinese National
Games last year, setting the world record of 4:34.79 in the 400m
individual medley.
</P>
<P>
"Chen Yan has talents for swimming," said Chen's coach Han
Bingyan. "She has long arm span, supurb techniques and very good
rhythm in water." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
