<HEADLINE> New Ambassador Pledges Work to Improve Sudan-Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Ambassador-designate to
Egypt Ahmed Abdel Halim said today he would work for improving
ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Abdel Halim, Sudan's former ambassador to Austria, made the
remarks during a few hours' stop-over at Cairo International
Airport early this morning before heading home at the end of his
duty in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat said he will return to Cairo in a few days to take
up his new post as Sudan's ambassador to Egypt.
</P>
<P>
"I hope I will help restore Egyptian-Sudanese relations back to
normal," he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed full confidence that these ties will improve
quickly as the two countries' leaders have expressed keenness on
turning a new leaf in relations between them.
</P>
<P>
The appointment of a new Sudanese ambassador to Egypt, which
reportedly will be followed by a similar move of Cairo, came amid
signs of a warm-up in Cairo-Khartoum relations.
</P>
<P>
Cairo has in the past accused Sudan of supporting Muslim
militants seeking to oust Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
install a purist Islamic state in Egypt. It has also charged
Khartoum with sheltering gunmen who tried to assassinate Mubarak
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Sudan has denied the charges and criticized Egypt for letting
Sudan's opposition in exile operate from Cairo.
</P>
<P>
The two neighboring countries are also at odds over a border
disput, but there have been signs of a tentative thaw in
relations.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Tayeb Youssef Kordofani, the former Sudanese ambassador,
has said that he was ending his three-year stint in Cairo "with
the hunch that Egyptian-Sudanese relations were returning to their
normal courses."
</P>
<P>
Osama el-Baz, Mubarak's Political Advisor, said recently
that Egypt expects the turning of "a new leaf" in its relations
with Sudan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
