<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barclays Sells Its Asian Equity Business to CSFB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Credit Suisse First Boston
(CSFB) will acquire Barclays PLC's selected investment banking and
equity businesses in Asia, the two companies announced here
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement, BZW, the investment banking arm of the
London-based Barclays, will see parts of its Asian businesses
being sold to CSFB, a leading global corporate and investment
banking firm wholly owned by the Zurich-based Credit Suisse Group.
</P>
<P>
CSFB will acquire BZW's Taiwan equity business, its 70 percent
interest in an equity joint venture in Singapore, and stock
exchange seats in Singapore, Hong Kong and Shanghai. The
businesses being sold had net assets of 14 million pound sterling
as at November 30, 1997, said a new release from BZW Asia Ltd.
</P>
<P>
A total of 200 staff will be transferred from BZW's offices in
Asia to CSFB, sources from CSFB, Hong Kong said.
</P>
<P>
Stephen Stonefield, chairman of CSFB in Asia Pacific, said:
"CSFB has been actively expanding in Asia since 1996 and this
acquisition complements our growth plans in the region."
</P>
<P>
The purchase of BZW's Asian businesses will enable CSFB to
expand its capability to all major stock exchanges in the region,
including Hong Kong, Tokyo, Osaka, Mumbai, Seoul, Taipei, Shanghai
and Singapore.
</P>
<P>
In the first three quarters of 1997, BZW was the fifth largest
equity issuer in the Asia Pacific market (excluding Japan), and
was ranked third in mergers and acquisition league tables.
</P>
<P>
CSFB acquired BZW's European equity and investment banking
businesses in November, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Barclays said in its news release that it will continue to
maintain a significant presence in the region through its capital,
private banking and asset management businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
