<HEADLINE> Nordic Stocks Seen Falling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, January 12 (Xinhua)-- Nordic stocks are seen falling
in the days ahead, as the deepening financial crisis in Asia is
set to continue hurting exporters such as engineering companies
Kvaerner and Asea Brown Boveri.
</P>
<P>
"What's happening in the Far East is definitely going to have
an effect on companies in the Nordic region," said Flemming
Barlett, chief equity trader at Den Danske Bank. "More defensive
stocks will do better, such as banks, food companies and
utilities."
</P>
<P>
Companies with a large part of their sales in Asia dropped the
most. Ericsson of Sweden fell 4.5 percent on Friday to 290
Swedish kronor, while its Finnish competitor Nokia dropped 3.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Swedish-Swiss engineering company Asea Brown Boveri's shares
fell 2.8 percent to 87.5 Swedish kronor, while Kvaerner, an
Anglo-Norwegian construction and shipbuilding company, slumped
9.2 percent to 322.5 Norwegian kroner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
