<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Keeps Above 64 US Cents level </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
above the crucial 64 US cents level for the first time in a week,
but could not sustain larger gains made at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The local unit closed at 64.08 US cents Monday, marginally
higher than 63.98 cents late Friday but down from 64.16 US cents
at the start of the session.
</P>
<P>
The currency was largely confined to a range of 64.05 US cents
to 64.25 US cents on Monday - relatively tight trading after last
week's large swings.
</P>
<P>
Traders said market participants were wary of testing the
Australian dollar's downside for fear of further Reserve Bank of
Australia (RBA) intervention.
</P>
<P>
Reported selling of US dollars and buying of Australian dollars
by the central bank on Friday sent the local currency soaring one
US cent during that session.
</P>
<P>
Sideways trading in the US dollar/Japanese yen also gave the
Australian dollar a breather after recent surges in the greenback
proved disastrous for the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
The market was awaiting the outcome of meetings between
political leaders in the Asia region. Of particular concern is
Indonesia where the rupiah halved its value in four days last
week.
</P>
<P>
However, Indonesian President Suharto Monday vowed to
accelerate reforms under an IMF rescue program as a high-level US
mission prepared to visit Jakarta to underscore concern and
support for the region.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended Monday at 84.69 yen, from 84.27
Friday, and at 1.1683 marks, from 1.1608.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
