<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks in Biggest Fall Since October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
Monday dived 2.3 percent in its biggest one day fall since the
October plunge last year on further fears of the Asian meltdown's
impact on the local economy and company performances.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index fell 60.7 points to 2542.4 - its
lowest level in three weeks - as Hong Kong shares plummeted more
than ten percent in morning trade on worry about regional
collapse, exchange rates and escalating interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Australian shares held up reasonably strongly in the face of
Hong Kong, with most of the all ordinaries fall coming in early
trade in reaction to Friday's sharp falls on Wall Street, which
lost 222 points, and futures-led selling.
</P>
<P>
"I think our market performed quite well today considering all
the things that happened with Wall Street and Hong Kong," Steve
Negrine from Reynolds and Co. said.
</P>
<P>
"There was a bit of weakness in the majors but it held up
reasonably well. I think the bonds rally has really helped us and
has provided some momentum," he said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index dropped 100.7 points to 4399.5, with
bigger stocks particularly being sold down.
</P>
<P>
Telstra installment receipts were one of the hardest hit, down
11 cents, and more than 20 million of the receipts were traded.
</P>
<P>
The major banks also fell sharply, with the most Asian exposed,
ANZ, falling 35 cents, Westpac lost 24.4 cents, National Australia
Bank fell 43.9 cents and Commonwealth Bank lost 50 cents.
</P>
<P>
Mining and resource stocks lost even more ground in the selling
market while gold stocks took a tumble on the weakening bullion
price.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index fell 29.4 points to 1054.9 with the
gold index closing 48.1 points lower at 951.6.
</P>
<P>
The gold bullion price fell 4.00 US dollars per ounce to
278.00.
</P>
<P>
National turnover for the day was 253.3 million shares at a
value of 741 million Australian dollars (474.24 million US
dollars) with falls outnumbering rises 859 to 323.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shipbuilding Business Soars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- China's shipbuilding output hit
an all-time high with a combined 2.29 million tons last year, up
20.5 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents a 5 percent share of the world
shipbuilding market and puts China in third place following Japan
and the Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
The figures were released at a national shipbuilding industry
meeting held here today. Vice-premiers Li Lanqing and Wu Bangguo
wrote congratulatory letters for the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The country sold a record 22 billion yuan worth-of vessels in
1997. Exported were 1.96 million tons of ships earning 1.5 billion
U.S. dollars worth of foreign currency, a year-on-year rise of
13.6 percent, according to Xu Penghang, general manager of the
China State Shipbuilding Corp. (CSSC).
</P>
<P>
The CSSC accepted 2.07 million tons of shipbuilding orders,
including 1.62 million tons of export-oriented vessels. The amount
of high-tech and high-added-value vessels -- such as liquefied
petroleum gas carriers, container vessels, and multi-purpose
vessels -- reached 850,000 tons, a rise of 16.3 percent from 1996.
</P>
<P>
A group of state key research projects -- including 150,000-ton
oil tankers, 52,000-ton multi-purpose ships, high-speed container
ships, and high-performance vehicles -- have been completed.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Shanghai's Waigaoqiao shipbuilding base has been
approved by the State Council. Work is nearly completed on a
100,000-ton building berth of the Bohai Shipbuilding Plant and a
150,000-ton dry dock of Shanhaiguan Ship Plant.
</P>
<P>
Xu said that China's shipbuilding output is expected to remain
at 2.3 million tons in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that during the Eighth Five-Year Plan
(1991-1995), the country built 6.76 million tons of ships,
representing a rise of 24 percent on a yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
According to a CSSC plan, China's shipbuilding output is
projected at three million tons in the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
