<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 21 More Kenyans Killed by Rift Valley Fever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The killer disease diagnosed
as Rift Valley fever claimed at least 21 more Kenyans in Garissa
and Wajir districts, Northeastern Province, in the last two days,
the Daily Nation newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
This brings to more than 350 the number of who have died since
the outbreak was first made public by Northeastern Provincial
Commissioner Maurice Makhanu in late December, said the report.
</P>
<P>
However, Red Cross Health Coordinator Saade Abdala, who
confirmed the deaths, said in Garissa town that the disease was
under control as those affected were being offered medical
attention and were not dying as quickly as before.
</P>
<P>
Most victims got the disease from handling ailing livestock,
she noted, suggesting local residents burn all carcasses.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic, which also affected livestock, was communicable
from livestock to human beings, said Abdala, who is in charge of
Red Cross activities in Garissa District and runs a treatment
camp for victims of the disease there.
</P>
<P>
Fresh rains have continued to pound the region in the past two
weeks and have flooded the area again, making the disease, which
had actually subsided, recur.
</P>
<P>
The disease, whose victims vomit, diarrhoea and bleed from
body orifices was diagnosed as the deadly rift valley fever by
medical experts following tests carried out in South Africa and
the United States.
</P>
<P>
The collection of blood samples from victims of the disease
for further specialized tests abroad is still on.
</P>
<P>
Rift Valley Fever is a viral disease transmitted by mosquitoes
and is predominantly found in domestic animals. It can also
affect human beings exposed to heavy infection by direct contact
with infected animals.
</P>
<P>
In 1977, the disease erupted in Egypt with 200,000 people
infected, out of whom 600 died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0127 </DOCNO>
