<HEADLINE> Australian Universities to Recruit More Fee-Paying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Australian universities would
be forced to recruit an additional 45,000 local and overseas
fee-paying students over the next three years in the wake of the
federal government's decision to freeze all future spending on
higher education, the Sydney Morning Herald reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
A report that was prepared for Education Minister David Kemp
also confirmed the number of publicly funded student places would
drop nationally by at least 1,700 within the next two years.
</P>
<P>
National Union of Students President, Rose Tracey said "Kemp's
plans are designed to fundamentally change the face of the
education sector in a bid to knock down the public sector wherever
it exists," Tracey said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Quite simply, more fees means less access," she said, "If this
trend continues there can be no doubt that no one but the very
rich or the very lucky will be able to get into university."
</P>
<P>
Opposition Education spokesman Mark Latham said the
government's decision to establish two tiers of access and
opportunity was unfair.
</P>
<P>
"It is plainly unfair for access to university now to be
determined by whether or not families have a spare 100,000
Australian dollars (65000 US dollars) with which they can buy a
student place," Latham said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"Hard working students who have studied well and achieved solid
school leaving results are being punished solely because they come
from a lower to middle income background," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that the Asian economic crisis would place more
pressure on our universities to make up for lost revenue by fees
paid by Australian students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
