<BODY>
<HEADLINE> California Firm to Start First Major Trial of AIDS Vaccine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 11 (Xinhua) -- A biotechnology unit based
in south San Francisco will put the first AIDS vaccine it has
engineered into human trial sometime this year, a local newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the San Jose Mercury News, the VaxGen Inc. study,
which will cost 20 million U.S. dollars and three years to
complete, is expected to involve 7,500 healthy volunteers.
</P>
<P>
Half the volunteers, of which, 5,000 would be in the United
States and 2,500 in Thailand, will get the vaccine while the other
half get placebos.
</P>
<P>
If successful, the vaccine, the key ingredient of which is a
protein that helps hold the AIDS virus together, would be
available to the public in the early part of the next century, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The vaccine, dubbed as AIDSVAX, uses the same gp120, which was
also the key ingredients of an earlier version. But the new
vaccine appears to be much more robust than the previous one which
was not considered encouraging by mixed results of studies.
</P>
<P>
Most of the volunteers to be involved in the test are
considered at high risk of contracting HIV. They would be tracked
for three years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ISO Certifies Swiss Bank's Environmental Management System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- The International Organization
for Standardization (ISO) has certified an environmental system of
the Swiss bank Credit Suisse, according to the January/February
issue of the ISO News magazine.
</P>
<P>
Having achieved ISO 14000 certification, the bank's
environmental objectives include replacing the use of fuel oil
with gas, reducing its electricity consumption by 10 percent
annually until 2004 and generating clean energy by installing
solar panels on the roof of its Geneva office.
</P>
<P>
As a result of these measures, which involve an investment of
30 million Swiss francs (about 20.5 million U.S. dollars), the
bank is expected to economize three million Swiss francs (about
2.05 million dollars) a year by 2004. 
</P>
</TEXT>
