<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Net Worth Rises to 1.2 Trillion US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Australia's net worth
increased to 1.9 trillion Australian dollars (about 1.21 trillion
U.S. dollars) by the end of June 1996, or the end of the fiscal
year of 1995-1996, official figures released Monday showed.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents a 2.1 percent increase over the previous
fiscal year ending June 30, 1995, a survey of the Australian
Bureau of Statistics (ABS) showed.
</P>
<P>
Households with assets such as bank deposits, superannuation,
land and housing contributed about three-quarters of the total
national net worth, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
Net worth was defined by the bureau as the difference between
total assets and liabilities including company shares.
</P>
<P>
"Australia's net worth was estimated at 1,909.5 billion
Australian dollars (about 1.21 trillion U.S. dollars) at the end
of June 1996," the ABS said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1990-1991 recession, Australia's net worth grew
continuously and consistently representing at least four times the
level of annual gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The strongest growth in Australia's net worth was exhibited
during the fiscal years from 1992-1993 to 1994-1995, when annual
rates of at least 4 percent were achieved, the ABS said.
</P>
<P>
Households and unincorporated enterprises recorded a 3 percent
increase in their net worth in fiscal 1995-1996, which rose to 1.4
trillion Australian dollars (896 billion U.S. dollars), accounting
for about three quarters of the national total.
</P>
<P>
Their major assets comprised land, housing, superannuation and
savings, with loans representing the major liability.
</P>
<P>
The value of Australia's total produced assets rose by 3.4
percent from a year earlier to 1,372.1 billion Australian dollars
(878 billion U.S. dollars) at the end of fiscal 1995-1996.
</P>
<P>
Australia's natural resources accounted for 822 billion
Australian dollars (526 billion U.S. dollars) of the net worth,
including total land value estimated at 408 billion U.S. dollars,
2.1 percent up from the level of 12 months earlier.
</P>
<P>
The value of minerals still below ground rose 3 percent to
114.8 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The general government sector accounted for roughly one-fifth
of Australia's net worth.
</P>
<P>
Securities, such as treasury bonds, was the principle liability
of the general government sector, although the ABS survey found
Australia's debt ratio was substantially lower than most
industrialized countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chen Wins Women's 400m Individual Medley </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 12 (Xinhua) -- World record holder Chen Yan of
China touched home first to lift the women's 400m individual
medley title at the world swimming championships here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old Chen timed four minutes and 36.66 seconds to
win China's first swimming gold medal at this championships.
</P>
<P>
Yana Klochkova finished second in 4:45.94 with Japanese Joanne
Malar third in 4:39.45.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Wu Yanyan, who led the field until the last 80 meters,
placed fourth in a time of 4:40.16.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yan began swimming at the age of 6 and joined the Liaoning
club in Northeast China at 12.
</P>
<P>
Chen jumped into fame in October 1995 when she won the 400m
individual medley, 200m and 400m freestyle events in the Chinese
City Games in Nanjing.
</P>
<P>
She reached the peak of her career in the Chinese National
Games last year, setting the world record of 4:34.79 in the 400m
individual medley. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
