<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Send Home 4,000 Filipino Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- At least 4,000 Filipino workers
who are currently working in Malaysia will be repatriated this
year, the official Philippine News Agency said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Ambassador to Malaysia Gregorio Brilliantes told the
news agency Monday that most Filipino workers to be affected by
Malaysia's gradual repatriation plan are those in the service
sector.
</P>
<P>
According to him, these workers will include some 1,000
construction workers, 2,000 from the hotel and leisure industries,
and 1,000 more from the domestic services such as housemaids.
</P>
<P>
Those to be repatriated are just a fraction of the more than
30,000 Filipino workers now working in different places of
Malaysia, he said.
</P>
<P>
Brilliantes said that the Malaysian government was forced to
repatriate foreign workers to protect its sagging economy as a
result of the falling Malaysian currency, the ringgit, which used
to be very strong.
</P>
<P>
Brilliantes said more overseas workers are expected to be sent
home by Malaysia this year because of its worsening economic
situation.
</P>
<P>
The report also said Indonesia, whose rupiah has devalued by
more than 177 percent since the crisis struck the country in July
1997, is likely to follow the lead of Malaysia and send some
Filipino workers home.
</P>
<P>
South Korea, one of the hardest-hit countries by the currency
crisis, is expected to send about 3,000 Filipino workers home
early this year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government is preparing all the necessary
measures to respond to the needs of the repatriated workers when
they get back, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has about 4.2 million workers working abroad,
mainly in Southeast Asia, the Middle East and North America, as
domestic helpers, construction workers, nurses and seamen.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, overseas Filipino workers sent home more than 5.7
billion U.S. dollars in remittances through banks, accounting for
5 percent of the country's gross national product last year.
</P>
<P>
Remittances from overseas workers have been a major source of
the Philippines' foreign reserves in recent years while the
country has been incurring a trade deficit.
</P>
<P>
The repatriation of more and more Filipino workers is expected
to reduce the dollar inflow to the country and increase the number
of unemployed people, economists said.  
</P>
