<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang's Oil Industry Developing Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The three oil fields in
northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region pumped 15.8
million tons of crude oil in 1997, an increase of 10 percent over
the 1996 figure. The output amounted to 11.5 percent of the
country's total onshore oil output.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, a total of 350 million tons of oil
reserves had been confirmed in the three oil fields in the
region's Tarim, Junggar and Turpan-Hami basins, today's People's
Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
This demonstrates that the oil industry in Xinjiang has entered
a period of rapid development, with last year's proven reserves
and the growth rate of crude oil output ranking first in the
country, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
Following the discovery of an oil field with reserves exceeding
100 million tons in the Junggar Basin, another large oil field in
Lukqun was found in the Turpan Basin near the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
China's oil industry, which now produces more than 140 million
tons of crude oil a year, has been stymied by inadequate
reserves. In the east, which provides 80 percent of the country's
oil, reserves have been declining by 20 million tons annually and
production costs have increased rapidly.
</P>
<P>
In response, China in the early 1990s turned to its western
areas for new resources, and oil exploration in the three Xinjiang
basins has entered a prosperous period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Wins First-ever Men's Swimming Medal in Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PERTH, January 12 (Xinhua) -- China won the first-ever men's
world championship swimming medal as Zeng Qiliang finished
runner-up to Olympic champion Frederik Deburghgraeve at the 100m
breaststroke event here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Belgian Deburghgraeve, world record holder and the Atlanta
Olympic gold medalist, touched the pad first in a time of one
minute and 1.34 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Zeng clocked 1:01.34 for the silver medal, breaking his own
Asian record of 1:01.66 set in the Chinese National Games last
year.
</P>
<P>
American Kurt Grote finished third in 1:01.93. 
</P>
