<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Output Value of Building Materials Increases 9.75 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- China's building materials
industry topped 310 billion yuan in output value for 1997, up 9.75
percent over 1996, according to Zhang Renwei, director of the
State Administration of Building Materials.
</P>
<P>
Speaking today at a national conference on building materials,
Zhang said China produced 510 million tons of cement last year, up
3.63 percent over 1996, and 146 million cases of flat glass, an
increase of 5.42 percent.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that in 1997 China's production of building
materials made the following gains:
</P>
<P>
-- The quality of the products improved, with the qualification
ratio arriving at nearly 90 percent;
</P>
<P>
-- The relationship between production and marketing improved;
</P>
<P>
-- Earnings from exports exceeded the 1996 figures. In 1997,
the earnings from exports of the country's building materials
stood at 2.48 billion U.S. dollars, up 14.77 percent over the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that this year China will support the development of
large building materials enterprises, improve industrial structure
and give priority to the development of quality cement and glass
urgently needed by the national economy, and for the construction
of key projects.
</P>
<P>
The country will also work diligently to develop new building
materials needed for residential buildings and interior
decoration, the official added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Bailout Terms Need Review: Thai Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Thai Finance Minister Tarrin
Nimmanhaeminda stressed Sunday that the conditions of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) bailout package for Thailand
need to be reviewed to fit changed circumstances.
</P>
<P>
He said that when Thailand accepted IMF assistance in August
last year, no one expected the current regional currency turmoil.
Since then, however, circumstances have changed and the conditions
need to be reviewed, the Nation newspaper quoted Tarrin as saying
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin, who is scheduled to visit the United States next Monday
to Wednesday, said he will discuss with IMF officials changes in
the country's monetary and fiscal policies.
</P>
<P>
Tarrin is to visit the United States at a time when the Thai
currency, the baht, has sunk to 53-54 baht to the U.S. dollar,
from 25.79 baht before its float last July and the IMF's
prescriptions for some Asian countries, including Thailand, are
under attack by top world economists.
</P>
<P>
These economists argue that the IMF is prescribing too much
austerity and will end up pushing recipient countries into severe
recession.
</P>
<P>
Critics believe that higher interest rates, less government
spending and increased taxes, as required by the IMF, will only
make the patients even sicker.  
</P>
</TEXT>
