<HEADLINE> 21 Kilograms of Heroin Seized in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-one kilograms of heroin
have been seized in western Turkey, the semi-official Anatolia
News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that the Turkish police had stopped a car at
Kapikule Border Gate in Edirne province and found the heroin in
the vehicle. But it did not say when the heroin was seized.
</P>
<P>
Two Romanians, who bought the heroin from somebody in
Istanbul, the largest city in Turkey, were detained, said the
agency.
</P>
<P>
Last Thursday, the Turkish police seized 480.7 kilograms of
pure heroin in a passenger bus from Baku, capital of Azerbaijan,
at the Sarp Border Gate on the Turkey-Georgia border.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is a key transit route of drugs to Europe from the area
bordering Afghanistan and Pakistan. In 1996, Turkish police
seized 4.4 tonnes of heroin, or 40 percent of the world's total
haul. 
</P>
</TEXT>
