<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Army Chief Meets with Former U.S. Defense Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- China wishes to maintain its
regular military-to-military dialogues and exchanges of visits of
high-ranking officials with the United States, the Chief of the
General Staff of the Chinese People's Liberation Army (PLA) Fu
Quanyou said here today.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with a delegation from the United States led
by former U.S. Secretary of Defense William Perry this morning, Fu
said the Chinese armed forces wish to conduct exchanges with the
U.S. military in broader fields.
</P>
<P>
Fu said China places importance on developing
military-to-military relations with the United States.
</P>
<P>
He expressed appreciation to the members of the U.S. delegation
for the efforts that they have made to improve and expand
relations between the two countries and their armed forces. He
also reviewed his visit to the United States last year.
</P>
<P>
Fu briefed his U.S. guests about the latest developments in
China's army building. He noted that at the 15th National Congress
of the Communist Party of China (CPC) last September, Chinese
President Jiang Zemin announced that China would downsize its
armed forces by another 500,000 in the next three years on the
basis of a 1-million-man cut in the 1980s. He said this move is a
major step that the Chinese army adopted to promote its striving
for quality, as well as a reflection of the Chinese people's
determination and earnest desire to maintain peace.
</P>
<P>
Perry said he will continue to contribute to the strengthening
of relations between the two countries and their armed forces. He
said he hoped that the United States would be able to assist the
modernization drive by China's army.
</P>
<P>
This is Perry's 10th visit to China in 17 years. He is here as
guest of the China Foundation of International Strategic Study.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
