<HEADLINE> Stocks Plunge in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Tokyo stock prices fell sharply
Monday with the key Nikkei index slipping to a two and half-year
low.
</P>
<P>
This happened on the market's disappointment over the lack of
fresh economic steps in Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto's Diet
(Parliament) speech earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section
at the Tokyo Stock Exchange plunged 330.66 points, or 2.21 percent
from last Friday's close to 14,664.44, the lowest since July 1995.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the First Section came to an estimated 310 million
shares, down from Friday's 399.79 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto's speech at the beginning of the regular Diet session
in the afternoon on economic and financial measures was out of
focus, and the decline of the benchmark index accelerated, traders
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
