<HEADLINE> Relief Supplies Transported to Quake-hit Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
By noon today Zhangbei had received relief goods from 121
organizations in different localities, according to officials with
the local donation center.
</P>
<P>
The supplies include food, cooking materials, medicine and
overcoats and quilts.
</P>
<P>
Tangshan city, which was devastated by a strong tremor
measuring 7.8 on the Richter scale in 1976, has sent 22 trucks of
relief goods worth 1 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
"We drove night and day without stopping. We had to run against
time," said driver Liu Hongwei, who left Tangshan for Zhangbei
Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said he saw several convoys with relief supplies all heading
to Hebei, including some from east China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
The People's Liberation Army troops stationed in Hebei Province
used helicopters to transport 25,000 kilograms of steamed bread
and pancakes to the quake-stricken areas on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Located at the conjunction of Beijing, Shanxi Province and
Inner Mongolia and 1,600 meters above sea level, the quake-hit
area is experiencing the coldest weather of the winter season,
with average daytime temperatures lingering around 10 degrees
below zero Centigrade.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the disaster relief center said they dispatched
the arriving trucks directly to townships and villages to ensure
people there receive timely help.
</P>
<P>
Saturday's earthquake claimed 47 lives, injured more than
10,000 people and destroyed tens of thousands of houses in
Zhangbei and neighboring Shangyi county. 
</P>
</TEXT>
