<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Denies Offer to Send Troops to S. Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, January 12 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine has denied that his country suggested sending troops to
south Lebanon in order to provide security in case of Israel's
pull-out from there, the Daily Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
On the first leg of his three-country regional tour, Vedrine
held talks with his Lebanese counterpart Fares Boueiz Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
At a joint news conference with Boueiz, Vedrine confirmed that
France has never made such a suggestion, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that his country is striving to produce a
fair solution for the Arab-Israeli conflict and achieve the
implementation of the United Nations Security Council resolution
425.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said he considers as "encouraging" Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai's offer last week to withdraw from
the security zone in south Lebanon provided Israel's northern
security is guaranteed by Lebanon,
</P>
<P>
Israel established the 1,200-square-kilometer security zone in
south Lebanon in 1985 with the aim of protecting its northern
areas from cross-border attacks by Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
However, Vedrine noted that "this statement is the first of its
kind and we should not forget that resolution 425 does not include
conditions."
</P>
<P>
The resolution, adopted in 1978 after Israel's invasion, calls
for an Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon without conditions,
and restoration of peace and security and the extension of
Lebanese authority over the region.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine also denied that he discussed the Israeli suggestion
with Syrian Vice President Abdul-Halim Khaddam during Khaddam's
visit to France last week.
</P>
<P>
Syria, which has about 40,000 troops in Lebanon, is the main
power broker in this country. Lebanon and Syria have been keeping
special relations and vowed to carry out negotiations
simultaneously with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the regional situation, the French minister said
that "I have previously expressed my sadness about the peace
process and the stalemate it is passing through but this does not
mean that I am pessimistic in the long run."
</P>
<P>
Vedrine, who is on a brief visit to Lebanon, arrived in Beirut
Sunday night. During his visit, he will also meet with Lebanese
President Elias Hrawi, House Speaker Nabih Berry and Prime
Minister Rafik Hariri.
</P>
<P>
After visiting Lebanon, he will leave for Syria and Jordan on
a peacemaking mission which has taken him to Israel, Palestinian
self-rule areas and Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
