<HEADLINE> China's "Space City" Attracts Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Xichang, known as China's
"space city" and capital city of the Liangshan Yi Nationality
Autonomous Prefecture in southwestern Sichuan Province, is making
a new effort to open wider to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
During the past year, the prefecture signed 117 cooperation
contracts, introducing an investment of one billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Construction of China's satellite launching base in the city
during the past three decades has greatly improved the local
infrastructure and made the city known as "Asia's Houston."
</P>
<P>
Now, the prefecture -- with potential hydropower capacity of 71
million kilowatts, 59 varieties of mineral resources and 80
percent of the province's nonferrous metal reserves -- is making
full use of the city's reputation to attract investors.
</P>
<P>
As a result, an American company committed 1.2 billion yuan to
build a hydropower station with a capacity of 200,000 kilowatts.
Other foreign multinational corporations and domestic investors
are expected to follow suit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
