<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: E. African Projects Get World Bank's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 12 (Xinhua) -- More and more private sector
projects in Kenya, Uganda and Tanzania, all the three members of
the East Africa Cooperation (EAC), have been getting funding from
the International Finance Corporation (IFC) over recent years.
</P>
<P>
More than 66 million Dollars have been committed by IFC, the
private sector lending arm of the World Bank, to projects in
Kenya since 1970, the East African weekly reported today.
</P>
<P>
Major projects in Kenya financed by the IFC include
Pan-African Paper Mills (EA) Ltd, whose cumulative loan since
1970 has reached 30 million Dollars, Magadi Soda Company Ltd with
nine million Dollars and Rift Valley Textiles Ltd with 2.1
million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Between 1984 and 1997, the IFC provided 25 million Dollars in
loans to more than 16 projects in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The biggest loan of 7.5 million Dollars issued to Uganda went
to sugar Corporation of Uganda Ltd in 1984, followed by 6.5
million Dollars to East African Glass Works Ltd in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, four Ugandan projects under Metro Hotel Ltd, Conrad
Plaza, Kiwa II Industries Ltd and Afritours &AMP; Travel Ltd
qualified for loans totalling 1.5 million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Among the Ugandan projects lined up for consideration this
year is Mosa Courts, which is seeking an 800,000-Dollar loan for
the expansion of its apartments in Kampala at a cost of 2.7
million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzania, five projects have been approved by the IFC. The
biggest, worth four million Dollars, went to Sunflag (Tanzania)
Ltd to streamline and expand its textile operations in the
northern Tanzanian town of Arusha.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania Data Network got 2.25 million Dollars to build and
operate a public data communications network for domestic and
international service.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's biggest beneficiary of all time is the Tourism
Promotion Services (T) Ltd which got a loan of eight million
Dollars in 1994.
</P>
<P>
There is no standard application form of IFC financing. A
company or entrepreneur, foreign or domestic, seeking to
establish a new venture or expand an existing enterprise can
approach IFC directly by requesting a meeting or by submitting
preliminary project information.
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent of IFC's funding required for lending is
borrowed in the international financial markets through public
bond issues or private placements, while the remaining 20 percent
is borrowed from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The IFC is the largest multilateral source of loan and equity
financing for private sector projects in the developing world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
