<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Foil Misuse of Official Cars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The South African
Transport Department is taking measures to curb the misuse of
official cars to save government expenditure, local daily the
Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
The transport department in Mpumalanga Province will install
electronic equipment on government cars in a bid to stop corrupt
officials from misusing them, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Most civil servants who were responsible for crashing or
abusing government vehicles, costing millions in repairing fees,
often drove these vehicles without permission, according to
Jackson Mthembu, a top official in transport department in the
province.
</P>
<P>
"We want to monitor how they were being driven, the kilometers
they traveled and the areas they visited," Mthembu said.
</P>
<P>
Reckless driving and general disregard for the province's
property had cost Mpumalanga Province more than 770,000 Rand
(154,000 U.S. Dollars) in repairs in the financial year up to
March 1997. In the following 10 months that figure rocketed to
1.1 million Rand (220,000 U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
These figures excluded some cases where vehicles were written
off as beyond repair.
</P>
<P>
In Gauteng, a major province where the administrative capital
of Pretoria and Johannesburg, the commercial and business center
in South Africa is situated, civil servants crashed more than six
government vehicles every day during the past financial year,
costing four million Rand (800,000 U.S. Dollars) in repairs.
</P>
<P>
Mthembu said Transport Minister Mac Maharaj and the provincial
governments throughout the country were treating the matter
seriously because of the financial implications.
</P>
<P>
Misuse of cars was "draining provincial and national
resources". "With the help of police, we have been impounding
cars taken without permits and are then charging the corrupt
officials," Mthembu said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Economy Growth Predicted Slower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Kenya
(CBK) downed its 1997 forecast for gross domestic product (GDP)
growth of Kenya to 3.2 percent from 3.6 percent in its January
monthly economic review.
</P>
<P>
The eastern African country saw 4.6 percent GDP growth rate in
1996 and was expecting growth to rebound to a higher level this
year.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's economy grew 3.2 percent from November 1996 to
November 1997, the same as in the year to October, according to
the CBK report, adding inflation stood at just 8.3 percent in the
year to December.
</P>
<P>
The bank blamed the fall on political uncertainty in an
election year, drought hitting agriculture in the first quarter
of 1997, declining investment, continuous power interruptions and
generally poor infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The suspended three-year 205-million-U.S.-Dollar aid package
by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) on July 31 and a wave of
political and ethnic violence around the same time sent investors
and tourists scurrying for the exits.
</P>
<P>
That sent the Kenyan Shilling into a tailspin, losing 25
percent of its value in August and recovered slightly later.
</P>
<P>
So far the CBK's efforts to stabilize the currency and keep
inflation in single digit through tight monetary policies have
been widely believed successful.
</P>
<P>
But the high interest rates which have accompanied the bank's
tight monetary policy have also contributed to the economic
slowdown, analysts warn.
</P>
<P>
New Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae, however, says he would
seek bipartisan support to solve the problems and steer Kenya's
economy to better times.
</P>
<P>
Nyachae's appointment was announced on Thursday after general
elections held on December 29 and 30 returned President Daniel
arap Moi to power for his fifth and final five-year term.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0170 </DOCNO>
