<HEADLINE> IMF Sets Date for Resumed Talks over Loans to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, January 12 (Xinhua) -- A team from the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) is set to visit Kenya on February 9 to resume
talks with new Kenyan Financial Minister Simeon Nyachae on a
suspended multi-million-Dollar loan program.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations between the two sides -- and a three-year
205-million-Dollar aid package -- were suspended last July when
the IMF said it was not convinced the Kenyan government was
committed to ending corruption.
</P>
<P>
The IMF experts are returning at the invitation of the Kenyan
government, in part to learn how and when Kenyan plans to
implement economic reforms which it has promised would be carried
out after the 1997 poll, said Goodall Gondwe, deputy director of
the IMF's Africa Department and the team's leader.
</P>
<P>
The IMF was happy with Kenya's energy sector reforms and
welcomed the new Anti-Corruption Authority although it wished to
discuss how the authority would operate, Gondwe said in an
interview with the weekly East African published today.
</P>
<P>
However, the fund was disappointed that Kenyan President
Daniel arap Moi, who won the multi-party poll held on December 29
and 30, has not issued a public statement supporting the
independence of the Kenya Revenue Authority (KRA), he noted.
</P>
<P>
He added that the IMF welcomed Nyachae's appointment and
considered him "a man who understands institutions and is a
stickler for legality."
</P>
<P>
An experienced and forceful Nyachae has been widely regarded
in the local business community as a command economy enthusiast
and a supporter of intervention.
</P>
<P>
Moi met with Gondwe and his team in coastal Mombasa in
September and agreed on measures to "strengthen management of the
energy sector, safeguard the independence of the KRA, ensure that
Anti-Corruption Authority would be independent and establish
accountability for past financial infractions."
</P>
<P>
Kenya promised to implement a series of reforms before and
after election and "a good deal" of what was promised had been
done, Gondwe said last week.
</P>
<P>
He said in September that substantive talks on a second-year
annually Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF)
arrangement would start only after the government took decisive
action on reform issues.
</P>
<P>
The IMF allowed the first year's agreement to lapse with the
disbursement of the initial 37-million-Dollar slice soon after
the three-year ESAF loan package was signed in April 1995. Kenya
failed to convince the IMF to release the second
37-million-Dollar loan which was lost.
</P>
<P>
Hopes now hinge on salvaging the remaining 148 million Dollars
and accompanying structural adjustment credits from the World
Bank.
</P>
<P>
New IMF guidelines on corruption say staff can recommend
halting a loan if they suspect poor governance is hurting
economic performance or threatening implementation of an IMF
refrom plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
