<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Carry out Four Large Meteorological Experiments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- China will carry out four
large-scale meteorological experiments in the Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau, the South China Sea, Huaihe River and the Taiwan Straits,
according to Guangming Daily.
</P>
<P>
The experiments, the largest in China's meteorological history,
will start in April and are expected to be completed by 2001, said
Wen Kegang, director of the State Meteorological Administration.
</P>
<P>
Wen said the experiments aim to study the following fields:
</P>
<P>
-- The influence of the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau on the global
environment and China's disastrous weather;
</P>
<P>
-- How monsoons in the South China Sea affect the outbreaks of
droughts and floods in China;
</P>
<P>
-- The relationship between the global climate and the rainy
season in April and May in the middle and lower reaches of the
Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
-- The interaction of the ocean, continent and atmosphere and
their influence on the climate in eastern Asia.
</P>
<P>
Wen said that the four experiments, which have their own
emphasis and intergrate with each other, will help further study
on monsoons and the disastrous weather in China. The result should
be improved the more accurate weather forecasts.
</P>
<P>
The four experiments will involve not only most provinces,
municipalities, and autonomous regions in China's interior areas
and the South China Sea, but also many countries and regions in
the Asia-Pacific region. More than 20,000 scientists and
technicians including 1,000 Chinese and 500 foreign scientists
will take part in the experiments.
</P>
<P>
State-of-the-art equipment will be used to study the
interaction between the continent and the atmosphere, and that
between the ocean and the atmosphere, the water system and the
ocean currents, said the newspaper.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Trying to Transfer Water from Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is planning
to transfer water from neighboring Lesotho to Johannesburg to
meet water shortage of the city, local daily the Star reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Rand Water, a water utility, said last week that its was
investigating the viability of a 2.5 billion Rand (500 million
U.S. Dollars) water pipe to carry water directly from the Lesotho
Highlands Water Scheme to a water purification plant just south
of Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
The 10 billion Rand (two billion U.S. Dollars) Lesotho
Highlands Water Scheme, which started its first water delivery
last week, transfers water from the Lesotho Highlands into the
Vaal River for use in the thirsty industrial regions of Gauteng
Province, South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Walter Coxon, Rand Water's chief development engineer, said if
water was piped directly from the highlands, it would flow
downhill virtually all the way to Johannesburg and would not have
to be pumped back uphill from the Vaal Dam as is presently the
case.
</P>
<P>
A pre-feasibility study had indicated that the utility could
make considerable energy savings if it eliminated the cost of
having to pump water up to Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
A detailed feasibility study was under way to investigate
whether the savings would outweigh the capital cost of building a
pipe, Coxon said.
</P>
<P>
The feasibility study, which has been under way for a year,
was expected to report its finding within a month. This would
allow the utility to make a decision on whether to proceed in the
second half of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
