<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Launch Forest Protection Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- China will reduce timber
production to protect natural resources and improve efficiency,
according to Chen Yaobang, Chinese minister of the Forestry, at
the conclusion of a recent forestry planning conference held in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The decision is in line with China's leaders' priorities on
protecting the environment and preserving natural forests, today's
People's Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to protecting primeval forests and
natural forests in the ecologically vulnerable regions, especially
those growing at the headwaters of big rivers and along both banks
of their upper reaches.
</P>
<P>
Efforts will be made to foster and protect these regions' water
resources as well as preventing land erosion and sand silt from
posing threats to production, lives, and large water resources
facilities.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will take steps to phase out logging in these
regions, where 60 percent of the country's natural forest
resources and varieties of species is concentrated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
