<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Aid to S. Africa Might Be Reduced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, January 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa could
continue to get aid from the European Union (EU) after 1999, but
the package might be reduced from the current level of 600
million Rand (122 million U.S. Dollars) a year, the Business Day
newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
The current EU aid program expires in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"The question is whether it (the aid) is specific to South
Africa or whether is part of the Lome Convention," the paper
quoted outgoing EU ambassador to South Africa, Erwan Fouere, as
saying at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Unlike other African nations, which receive aid from the EU
via the convention, South Africa gets bilateral development
assistance from Brussels.
</P>
<P>
Fears have been expressed that the EU's eastward enlargement
could put pressure on its budgetary resources, resulting in less
funds being made available for former aid partners.
</P>
<P>
Fouere said future aid would have to focus on sectors that
would help South Africa stand on its own economically, such as
the promotion of small businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
