<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Suggests Forum for Nile River Waters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Foreign Minister
Seyoum Mesfin has underlined the need to set up a forum to devise
mechanisms for the equal share of the waters of River Nile among
all riparian countries.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with local Efoyita magazine, Seyoum said Egypt
has been preoccupied with projects from which it would be the
sole beneficiary impeding the realization of an agreement that
paves the way for a just utilization of the waters by all Nile
Basin countries.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian News Agency reported that unless viable
conditions are created among the riparian countries to forge an
agreement that guarantees equitable share of the waters, others
could follow suit to Egypt subsequently resulting in disputes
among the concerned countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said, Ethiopia is not of the opinion that both
White and Blue Nile are the natural resources of an individual
country and upholds the stand that the waters are the common gift
to all the riparian countries which should be used in a way
benefiting all parties.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia, he said, a country affected by recurrent droughts
should make use of its water resources in a bid to achieve food
self sufficiency as it would be rather difficult to bring about
sustainable agricultural development relying on rain-fed farming
alone.
</P>
<P>
The demand in Ethiopia for energy supply which is crucial for
development in the industrial, economic and social sectors has
been steadily growing, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has no intention of jeopardizing the interest of
others while seeking its own advantages, it wishes to cooperate
among countries.
</P>
<P>
The issue of the waters of River Nile is key to any form of
cooperation between Ethiopia and Egypt, he said, adding that an
agreement in principle with regard to the issue would open up the
opportunity to further promoting bilateral ties in other fields
of endeavor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0187 </DOCNO>
