<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, January 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING -- The Ministry of Civil Affairs has sent working
groups to earthquake-hit Zhangjiakou Prefecture, Hebei province,
to offer sympathy to victims and coordinate relief efforts.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Affairs Ministry said that medical facilities and
medicines are in short supply because of the large number of the
wounded, and more food is also needed. Thousands of people became
homeless after the earthquake last Saturday which killed 47
people, and efforts are being made to build makeshift shelters for
them to survive the severe winter season. (China-Hebei-Earthquake
Relief)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SINGAPORE -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong said
Southeast Asia is facing its "gravest" crisis and biggest test
since the end of World War II and called on the United States,
Japan, and Europe to rescue the region's troubled economies.
</P>
<P>
According to the Straits Times on Monday, Goh said the
worsening currency crisis in Southeast Asia is a "systemic
problem," which he called one of confidence and market sentiment.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a keynote address to a closed-door ruling People's
Action Party convention on Sunday, Goh, who is the party's
secretary-general, stressed that the market has to be calmed.
Confidence in currencies has to be restored through taking painful
and necessary measures prescribed by the International Monetary
Fund. (Singapore-Goh-Crisis)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- The fourth Pacific Dialogue, an annual
gathering of prominent regional economic and security experts,
opened here Monday to discuss the financial turmoil crisis in
Southeast and East Asia.
</P>
<P>
The two-day conference, chaired by Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim, is set to discuss the currency and stock
market problems facing the countries in Southeast and East Asia
and issues pertaining to cooperation in regional security, culture
 and civilization. (Malaysia-Pacific Dialogue)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- About 83 percent of Cuba's 7.8 million eligible
voters took part in the national and provincial assembly elections
Sunday, the National Electoral Commission said.
</P>
<P>
Cubans will select 601 deputies for the National Assembly of
People's Power and 1,192 representatives for 14 provincial
assemblies. Cuban President Fidel Castro cast his ballot in the
eastern province of Santiago de Cuba, where his name was listed on
the ballot. (Cuba-Election) 
</P>
