<HEADLINE> IMF Optimistic About Indonesia's Restructuring Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Deputy Managing Director of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) Stanley Fischer expressed
optimism here on Monday that the Indonesian government will
succeed in restructuring the country's financial sector.
</P>
<P>
"President Soeharto's explanation was clear that Indonesia will
implement this (restructurization) program. There is no ambiguity
on that," he told the press after paying a courtesy call on the
president.
</P>
<P>
At their 45-minute meeting, Fischer said the discussion between
the Indonesian government and the IMF would go into details when
IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus arrives here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We discussed more about how to implement the program (to
restructure the financial sector) set up by the Indonesian
government," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fischer, who arrived here on Sunday at the head of an IMF team,
held discussion with some Indonesian government ministers Sunday
afternoon on the country's economic situation. He said last night
that the talks were making progress.
</P>
<P>
Fischer said President Soeharto briefed him about the proposed
state budget for fiscal year 1998-99, which amounted to 135
trillion rupiah (one U.S. dollar equals 4,000 rupiah).
</P>
<P>
Fischer, however, refused to explain the IMF's position on the
state budget.
</P>
<P>
The IMF envoy came to Indonesia after the sudden fall of the
Indonesian rupiah, which declined to a historic low of 11,000 to
the U.S. dollar last Thursday. The rupiah has devalued by more
than 200 percent against the greenback since July last year.
</P>
<P>
At the end of October last year, the IMF along with the World
Bank and the Asian Development Bank agreed to provide 23 billion
U.S. dollars in financial and technical loans to Indonesia to help
overcome its monetary crisis, and Indonesia made a commitment to
conducting a series of economic reforms.  
</P>
</TEXT>
