<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Server of 'Science' Magazine Begins Operation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The China server of the
American magazine, Science, co-sponsored by the State Natural
Science Fund Committee (SNSFC) and other Chinese governmental
organizations, began operation today at Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
The server will provide researchers and students in China free
access to the lastest edition of "Science" on both the China
Science and Technology Network and China Education and Research
Network, said Zhang Cunhao, chairman of SNSFC.
</P>
<P>
Users of the China server of "Science" will also receive
additional information available on the magazine's Internet
edition, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The opening of the server has built a bridge for the exchange
of scientific information between China and the United States,"
Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
"Science," a weekly publication, enjoys a high reputation in
international scientific research circles and is especially known
for its articles on biology and medical science. It has a large
group of readers not only in China but also worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that an average of 2,000 people read "Science"
through the China Server each day during its trial
operation. Experts predicted that the number would keep growing
after the server formally began operations today.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the China Server of "Science" signifies "the
importance and the tremendous future of Sino-U.S. scientific
cooperation," said Chang-Lin Tien, the first foreign Academician
of the Chinese Academy of Sciences and former president of the
University of California, Berkeley, in the San Francisco Bay Area
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
"It will help provide the most-advanced and updated scientific
information for the world's most populous country at the minimum
cost and fastest speed," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
