<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Upgrades Weather Forecast, Surveillance System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai has established one
of the world's most advanced weather surveillance and forecast
system, according to a local meteorological official.
</P>
<P>
The modern weather surveillance and forecast centre was
equipped with sophisticated devices at a cost of 80 million yuan
(9.6 million U.S. dollars), including an advanced Weather
Surveillance Radar-88 Doppler (WSR-88D) imported from the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Wang Lei, director of the Municipal Meteorological
Administration, said the center's completion has greatly improved
the city's ability to forecast dangerous weather.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai boasts a history of more than 120 years of weather
forecasting since an observatory was built in Xujiahui in 1872.
At present, the city is the weather forecast center for east
China's six provinces, providing comprehensive meteorological
services such as numerical weather prediction for 41 cities in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that the Municipal Meteorological Administration has
set many records in China's meteorological services. It has carried
out the longest consecutive meteorological observation; it was the
first to establish a meteorological alarm system; and it was the
first to experiment with artificial rainfall.
</P>
<P>
During the testing of the WSR-88D and the whole system in the
past year, the accuracy of 24-hour weather forecasts has increased
from 80 percent to 90 percent, and the forecast accuracy of
typhoons, rainstorms, high temperature, cold waves, tornados and
other disastrous weather has risen from 71 percent in 1994 to 84
percent last year. Forecast errors were also greatly reduced.
</P>
<P>
Last August the city was hit by the strongest typhoon in the
1990s, but the damage to the city was minimized because of an
accurate forecast.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that Shanghai would introduce large-scale computers
and other advanced equipment in the future to further improve its
weather forecast accuracy, and would continue such experiments as
artificial fog dispersal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
