<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More American Travelers Bypass Travel Agencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Americans nowadays do not
have to rely on agents who make travel arrangement for them as
they have found other ways to save money.
</P>
<P>
For instance, they could check Web sites set up by airlines and
see whether there are cheap last-minute Internet specials on
unsold seats.
</P>
<P>
Last year, about four million air tickets, or one percent of
the total, were transacted via the Internet in the United States,
according to a report from the Air Transport Association.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year, some 13.4 million Americans will buy
tickets on-line, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts noted that when travel agents began to charge
customers additional fees, more and more Americans might choose to
buy tickets directly from airlines' toll-free numbers or via the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, an estimated half of the
travel agents on the U.S. west coast have begun charging
"processing fees" tacked onto the regular cost of a ticket or
reservation, which range between 5-40 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The analysts said that the number of such agents, who have been
suffering from cuts of commissions by airlines, is to grow, which
will lead to the fact that more and more travelers opt to bypass
travel agents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0201 </DOCNO>
