<HEADLINE> Residents of Northeast China Province Change Spending Patterns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Urban residents in northeast
China's Liaoning Province, a traditional industrial center, have
changed their pattern of buying consumer goods with the increase
of their income.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the ratio of urban residents' expenditures
on food, clothes and commodities for daily use dropped from 87
percent in 1985 to 76 percent in 1996. However, the ratio of their
expenditures on apartments, medical care, transportation and
services increased from 12 percent to 23 percent during the
1985-1996 period.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the income of the province's urban
residents increased at an average annual rate of 14.3 percent in
recent years. By 1996, per-capita income for urban residents had
reached 4,210 yuan (507 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Local residents also have more choices in buying goods as the
variety of commodities increases.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 for every 100 households in the province's urban areas
there were 93 color TV sets, 69 refrigerators and 86 washing
machines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
