<HEADLINE> Prisoners Take Over Colombia Jail for Better Conditions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- More than 300
prisoners, after holding a guard hostage, took over part of a
Colombia prison Sunday, in an attempt to seek better prison
conditions, police said.
</P>
<P>
Joined by more than 500 of their women relatives, these
prisoners at the San Isidro jail in Popayan, 370 kilometers
southwest of the capital, demanded improved conditions and more
visits, as well as an end to overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
The women relatives were at the prison during Sunday visiting
hours.
</P>
<P>
The prisoners and their family members asked the Red Cross and
national ombudsman's office to negotiate, police said.
</P>
<P>
Authorities had surrounded the prison. Three women, one of them
pregnant, left the jail after the takeover. No bloodshed was
reported.
</P>
<P>
Colombia's prisons currently hold 43,000 inmates, far more than
the 29,000 it was built to house. Although the Congress passed a
law in December to ease overcrowding by granting early release to
some prisoners, legal red tape has kept most of the releases
stranded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
