<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southeast Asia in "Gravest Crisis," Singapore Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Prime Minister Goh
Chok Tong said Southeast Asia is facing its "gravest" crisis and
biggest test since the end of World War II and called on the
United States, Japan, and Europe to rescue the region's troubled
economies.
</P>
<P>
According to the Straits Times on Monday, Goh said the
worsening currency crisis in Southeast Asia is a "systemic
problem," which he called one of confidence and market sentiment.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a keynote address to a closed-door ruling People's
Action Party (PAP) convention on Sunday, Goh, who is the party's
secretary-general, stressed that the market has to be calmed.
Confidence in currencies has to be restored through taking painful
and necessary measures prescribed by the International Monetary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. and Japan should work together to help restore market
confidence and to rescue the troubled economies. Europe should
also join in," he said.
</P>
<P>
The financial crisis would create tension within the region and
between the region and its major partners the United States and
Japan, he warned.
</P>
<P>
"It is in every one's interest to help calm down the situation
and lessen the danger of economic meltdown leading to political
turmoil," Goh emphasized, adding that Asian economies must of
course help themselves.
</P>
<P>
The Straits Times noted that Goh's message came just a few days
after he received a phone call last Thursday from U.S. President
Bill Clinton, who reiterated America's support for the programs
the IMF has tailored for the region.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also said he is optimistic that Singaporeans
would "more than survive" the current crisis, as the country has
paid close attention to sound fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
"In a crisis, a country's leadership and people are tested.
There is no crisis in Singapore. But if the region is in economic
difficulties and gripped by political turmoil, we will be
affected. We can expect tough times ahead," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
