<HEADLINE> Anti-Crime Committee Set Up in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Albania has decided to set up an
anti-crime committee, composed of senior officials, to further
reinforce the struggle against organized crime, the newspaper Koha
Jone (Our Times) said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Arbeng Jata, advisor to Albanian Prime
Minister Fatos Nano on security issues, as saying Saturday that
the committee will not have a chairman.
</P>
<P>
Kastriot Islami, the state minister under direct control of the
prime minister, will act as the coordinator of the committee.
</P>
<P>
Other members include Arben Imami, state minister for relations
between legal reforms and the People's Assembly, Neritan Ceka,
minister of the interior, Ndre Legisi, state secretary for the
Interior Ministry, and some senior officials from the Ministry of
Defense and intelligence agencies.
</P>
<P>
The major task of the committee is to coordinate the activities
of all anti-crime government organs and draft relevant laws.
</P>
<P>
Jata said that the decision of establishing such a committee
was made by Nano.
</P>
<P>
In recent weeks, organized crime and terrorist attacks became
rampant in Albania. Some policemen were killed or injured by
terrorists. 
</P>
