<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Corps Leads China In Cotton Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Xinjiang Production and
Construction Corps, China's largest state farm, harvested 1,435
kilograms of cotton per hectare in 1997, 50 kilograms more than
the national average to rank first in China.
</P>
<P>
The corps, located in the northwestern Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, is the country's largest enterprise in
agriculture, industry, commerce and trade. Ninety percent of the
corps members are engaged in agricultural production and
management.
</P>
<P>
The corps planted more than 300,000 hectares of cotton in 1997
and harvested 450,000 tons of cotton, accounting for nearly 40
percent of the region's total, according to Hu Zhaozhang, deputy
commander of the corps.
</P>
<P>
The state designated the corps as one of China's cotton
production unit in 1995. The corps, in turn, began developing
cotton as its pillar industry, setting a goal of 500,000 tons of
cotton by the turn of century.
</P>
<P>
Hu said the increased production resulted from the widespread
application of advanced cotton-growing techniques and research
achievements, including new varieties and plastic sheeting used on
98 percent of the cotton acreage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
