<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industrial Projects Launched In Hainan's Economic Development Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The 31-sq.km. Yangpu Economic
Development Zone in South China's Hainan province, on the Beibu Gulf,
has launched five large pioneering industrial projects, according to Wang
Yongchun, head of the zone.
</P>
<P>
Yangpu was approved as an economic development zone by the
State Council in 1992 and was China's first industrial zone solely
developed by foreign investors, with one of the most favorable
open policies in the country.
</P>
<P>
The first project, a 30-million-US-dollar grain processing
plant, began operation at the end of 1997, using new
technology to process 300,000 tons of rice every year, 70
percent of it for export.
</P>
<P>
The second, a Singapore-funded pulp plant, the largest in China,
involving an investment of 1.28 billion US dollars and having an
annual capacity of 600,000 tons of bleached pulp has begun
construction with the approval of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
There is also a high-speed wire plant, an oak panel plant, and
a float glass factory. Negotiations are also underway on oil-gas,
steel, and iron plant projects at a combined cost of seven billion
US dollars, Wang says.
</P>
<P>
Four billion HK dollars have been used over the past five years
for infrastructure construction, and the zone now has a
315,500-kilowatt power plant, an expressway to the provincial
capital of Haikou, and a modern post and telecommunications
project under development. The zone has completed the first phase
of construction work on Yangpu port.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
