<HEADLINE> Minsheng Bank Sees Growing Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The China Minsheng Banking
Corp, China's only non-state bank, registered a satisfactory
development record in its first two year's operation, a leading
bank official was quoted as saying in today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The Minsheng's assets have topped 20 billion yuan at the end of
1997, up from 1.3 billion yuan at the bank's opening in January
1996.
</P>
<P>
Pre-tax profits for 1997 are expected to surpass 200 million
yuan, said the official, adding that the figure will grow to 300
million yuan this year.
</P>
<P>
Minsheng was launched by private Chinese entrepreneurs' chamber
of commerce, the All-China Federation of Industry and Commerce. So
far, nearly half of its loans went to private firms.
</P>
<P>
The official said that the bank will continue to hold a leading
position in supporting private firms.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank official, the bank plans to launch some
impressive projects this year in providing financial support to
these firms.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the bank will be increasingly cautious in granting
new loans for good assets quality.
</P>
<P>
So far, the overdue loans only accounted for two percent in its
lending.
</P>
<P>
Minsheng is preparing for a capital enlargement, with an
anticipated equity investment from the International Finance Co,
the private sector arm of the World Bank, the official noted.
</P>
<P>
He also said the bank will continue to seek development in the
coastal regions and big cities. The bank has opened branches in
Shanghai, Shenzhen, Guangzhou and Wuhan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
