<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Reason to Devalue Renminbi: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 12 (Xinhua) -- China has no reason to
depreciate its currency, the renminbi yuan, in a market where the
supply of US dollars significantly exceeds demand, an government
official was quoted in today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The official from the China Foreign Exchange Trading System
said that by far, sellers of US dollars outnumber buyers. "We
should not devalue the yuan," he said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, turnover in the system totalled 69.7 billion US
dollars. The yuan closed at 8.2796 to the dollar last week.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that since 1994, when China devalued the yuan
to 8.7 against the US dollar and replaced its dual-rate system
with the new regime, the yuan has always been under the pressure
of appreciation, largely due to excessive market supply.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank of China, the nation's central bank, had to
buy the oversupply to maintain balance in the market. That has
helped push the country's foreign exchange reserve to 140 billion
US dollars at the end of 1997 from 105 billion US dollars at the
beginning of last year.
</P>
<P>
Chinese officials have repeatedly rebutted speculations that
the country might devalue the yuan to help China's exports remain
competitive while other currencies in the region nosedived to
record lows. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gansu Making Gains in Anti-Poverty Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Gansu Province helped more than
910,000 local people rise above the poverty line in 1997 despite
continued drought conditions.
</P>
<P>
People still living below the national poverty line in this
inland northwest province has been reduced to 2.84 million, or
14.2 percent of the rural population.
</P>
<P>
With more than 70 percent of the rural population living below
the poverty line two decades ago, Gansu has been a focal point of
the country's poverty relief campaign.
</P>
<P>
Years of effort has paid off. By 1994, the number of people
suffering from insufficient food and clothing dropped to four
million, with most of those living in remote mountain areas.
</P>
<P>
Though the province suffered from three consecutive years of
drought, the fight against poverty remained persistent and
successful, with efforts concentrating on support for farming,
breeding and infrastructure projects.
</P>
<P>
The province issued low-interest loans worth 485 million yuan
(58 million U.S. dollars) to poor areas and sent more than
10,000 officials to assist in 6,600 impoverished villages. The
per-capita annual income in the poor areas rose to 570 yuan (68
U.S. dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
