<HEADLINE> Howard, Soeharto Discuss Economic Crisis on Phone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard called Indonesian President Soeharto on Sunday to express
concern over the economic crisis in Indonesia, the official Antara
News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Howard called Soeharto on Sunday morning, said the report. But
it did not give details of their talks.
</P>
<P>
This was the second call to Soeharto by a foreign government
leader. On Friday, U.S. President Bill Clinton also spoke to
Soeharto on the phone about the economic situation in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
In their 25-minute conversation, Clinton said he believed
Indonesia will overcome its monetary crisis. He urged the
Indonesian government to push forward its economic reform program,
which it has agreed to in exchange for a 23 billion U.S. dollar
bailout package from the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, IMF special envoy Stanley Fisher held talks on
Sunday here with Indonesian government officials on the country's
economic situation. The envoy, who arrived here Sunday morning,
will meet Soeharto on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The telephone conversations between Soeharto and foreign
leaders and the IMF envoy's visit to Indonesia followed a sudden
fall of the Indonesian currency, the rupiah, which declined to a
record low of 11,000 per U.S. dollar last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has depreciated by more than 200 percent against the
dollar since July last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
