<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Raise Structural Steel Imports Duty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will raise the duty on
structural steel imports to 10 percent from the current level of
2-3 percent to curb dumping by foreign producers, according to a
Customs Department official.
</P>
<P>
The current duty of 40 satang per kilogram or 2-3 percent of
import value is not sufficient to protect the country against
dumping, especially by Korean producers.
</P>
<P>
The official was quoted Monday by the local press as saying
local manufacturers would not exploit the situation by raising
steel prices if the higher duties are imposed. For one thing,
steel demand is still far below supply due to the economic slump.
</P>
<P>
The proposed 10-percent duty is in line with the customs tariff
structure which taxes semi-finished products at between 10 and 20
percent.
</P>
<P>
Local manufacturers, citing high water and electricity costs
among other factors, have complained frequently about dumping and
lack of protection from the government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
