<HEADLINE> Overseas Investment Increases In Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, January 12 (Xinhua) -- Some Korean and Japanese
investors seem unaffected by the financial turmoil back home and
are doing well in the Chinese port city of Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Tianjin was one of the first cities to open up in China and has
had one of the country's fastest growing economy, with
double-digit GDP growth for five successive years.
</P>
<P>
Because of its potential, 11,400 overseas-backed companies have
been set up here, with 20 billion U.S. dollars worth of
investment, and 200 of the world's top 500 multinationals have
invested in 300 companies in Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors are reportedly satisfied with Tianjin's
investment environment, according to municipal government
officials, who have regular talks with them. The result has been
an additional 300 million U.S. dollars in investment from 70
companies last year. The US's Motorola has expanded its investment
in Tianjin from 120 million dollars to 1.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The overseas capital has helped meet the economic development
needs of the city, which uses 2.4 billion dollars of foreign
capital annually from more than 90 countries. In recent years,
overseas funds provided a third of Tianjin's total investment in
fixed assets. Last year, overseas-financed companies had 40
percent of the city's industrial output value and accounted for
more than 60 percent its five billion dollars worth of
exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
