<HEADLINE> Shanghai Leveling Shops To Build Gardens In Downtown Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, January 12 (Xinhua) -- A green project to pull down a
number of shops and stores on Nanjing Road, downtown Shanghai's
commercial center, has started this year.
</P>
<P>
The leveling of the shops and stores that are currently
generating 10,000 yuan (1,200 US dollars) of profit per square
meter annually is to provide rooms for gardens, trees and flowers.
</P>
<P>
One shop with annual sales of nearly 700 million yuan will be
moved to make way for a 20-hectare garden. Its owner, Han
Binsheng, said, "Although moving off the road is a big loss for
us, it's a good thing for the whole city."
</P>
<P>
In addition to the construction of ten 3,000-sq.m. green areas
in the downtown area, there will also be a 100 meter-wide and
97-km-long green belt along the city's outer ring road.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the Shanghai municipal government issued regulations
governing afforestration and green-up management which stipulate
that there should be no less than 30 percent green coverage in any
new residential quarters.
</P>
<P>
For the past three years, the green area coverage per capita
has grown by 0.3 sq.m. annually, and the city with a population of
14 million is on its way to increasing urban green coverage to
20.02 percent by the end of the century, giving 3.5 sq.m. per
capita.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
