<HEADLINE> Northeast Chinese City Outlines Development Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, January 12 (Xinhua) --Shenyang, capital of Liaoning
Province, is working toward becoming a modern metropolis in the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
Mayor Mu Suixin made that pledge in a speech this month given
at the first session of the 12th people's congress of Shenyang.
</P>
<P>
Shenyang will make great efforts to improve its infrastructure
in the next few years, Mu said, the establishment of an efficient
transportation network in the downtown areas, in particular. The
mayor also vowed to build more apartments and to improve
telecommunications facilities.
</P>
<P>
By 2002, per-capita living space will reach nine square meters
in the city, and the daily water supply volume in the urban areas
will reach 2 million cubic meters, he said. Cooking gas will be
available in more than 1 million urban households and the
availability rate of telephone lines will be 40 percent along with
an ample power supply.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the city will redouble its efforts to control
environmental pollution and to improve the surroundings, making
the city a hygienic place to live, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Mu noted that the city also plans to bring water pollution
under control in the Liaohe River by 2002, and industrial
pollutants will be discharged after proper treatment, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the city expanded 36 roads and built 1,525
kilometers of new highways. The city also had relocated 87
enterprises which had disturbed life of urban dwellers and shut
down 72 enterprises that caused serious pollution.
</P>
<P>
It has also increased heat supply area by 5 million square
meters, completed the first-phase project of improvements to the
Xinkai River and added 8 million square meters of green area.
</P>
</TEXT>
