<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Lowers GNP Target for 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
further scaled down the gross national product (GNP) growth target
for 1998 to 3 to 4 percent from 4 to 4.5 percent because of the
deepening currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Development Budget Coordinating Committee is also expecting
a higher inflation rate of 7.5 to 8.5 percent from an earlier
target of 6.5 to 7.5 percent, the local newspaper Manila Standard
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Citing a preliminary report from the inter-agency committee,
the newspaper said the full impact of the currency crisis on
consumer prices and the economy in general would be felt this
year.
</P>
<P>
Socioeconomic Planning Secretary Cielito Habito said earlier
that the expected slowdown in domestic output would be caused by
the high interest rates which discourage investments and the El
Nino phenomenon which would reduce agricultural growth.
</P>
<P>
The government economic managers had already substantially
reduced the original GNP target of 6.5 to 7.5 percent for 1998 in
late December 1997 and the initial inflation target of 6 to 7
percent last August.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Development Bank (ADB) predicted the country's
inflation to hit double-digit levels this year, fueled by the peso
depreciation and spending related to the May presidential polls.
</P>
<P>
But the ADB estimate of about 4 to 4.5 percent GNP growth for
the country this year is closer to the government's targets.
</P>
<P>
GNP sums up all goods and services produced by a country,
including income from abroad. Inflation, on the other hand, shows
how fast consumer prices have risen.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
