<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Review Anti-Dumping Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
review its anti-dumping laws as other Asian countries hit by the
currency crisis are expected to dump cheap products into the
country, local press reports said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Trade and Industry Secretary Cesar Bautisa was quoted as saying
the review would be aimed at shortening the time for processing
anti-dumping cases from the present 150 days to 60 days to the
benefit of local businessmen.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to have simpler anti-dumping procedure which
will benefit our local businessmen in a much shorter time. Because
of delays and tedious proceedings, businessmen are saying that by
the time the government is able to resolve the issue, the damage
has already been done," Bautisa said.
</P>
<P>
Asian countries such as South Korea and Thailand, two of the
most battered economies in the region, are expected to
aggressively export their products below their normal cost just to
liquefy their assets and pay their obligations.
</P>
<P>
The shorter anti-dumping procedure would not run counter to the
Philippines' commitment to the World Trade Organization, according
to Bautisa.
</P>
<P>
Bautisa admitted that in fact, local industrialists have
already complained to the government that the Philippines has
become a junkyard for cheap Asian goods.
</P>
<P>
The Federation of Philippine Industries earlier asked the Trade
and Industry Department for tougher anti-dumping laws to
discourage countries experiencing currency problems from flooding
the domestic market with cheap goods.
</P>
<P>
The federation complained that South Korea and other countries
with currencies that were depreciating faster than the Philippine
peso were dumping cheap goods into the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
Appliances and other goods from South Korea are reported being
sold here at dirt-cheap prices, with some retailers offering a
free television set for every two bought.
</P>
<P>
Dumping occurs when imported items are priced lower than in the
countries where these goods come from and when the difference in
prices is harming local industries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
