<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Sovereignty over Tibet Brooks No Dispute(1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing, January 12 (Xinhua) -- An American student named
Joseph Yu Kuo at Yale University recently sent a letter to China's
English weekly Beijing Review, to discuss China's sovereignty over
Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The letter is to be carried on the January 12-18 issue of the
weekly.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Yu Kuo who is double-majoring in East Asian studies and
history said, "I did a great deal of research and have written an
article refuting the current incorrect beliefs and accusations of
the so-called 'human rights activists' for Tibet and their cohorts
in the U.S. government while affirming China's sovereignty and
record of governance in Tibet."
</P>
<P>
On China's sovereignty over Tibet, Joseph Yu Kuo said that this
is abundantly confirmed through historical facts.
</P>
<P>
He said that as early as in the 7th century the King of Tibet,
then Sontsen Gampo, assumed the role of a vassal ruler to the Tang
Dynasty of China through his acceptance of such Imperial Chinese
titles as "Commandant-escort" to Emperor Gaozong and his payment
of tribute to the central government of China.
</P>
<P>
By the early 9th century, the Tibetan and Chinese governments
had forged a formal political alliance, in which the two parties
pledged "amity as though they were of one family", said the
article.
</P>
<P>
Both the Ming and Qing Dynasties further affirmed Chinese
sovereignty over Tibet from the mid-14th Century until the
beginning of the 20th century, he continued.
</P>
<P>
The Ming Dynasty recognized the status of the Dalai Lamas by
conferring upon them various supplemental titles after receiving
their tributary payments.
</P>
<P>
The Qing government of China appointed an Imperial Resident
Commissioner in 1727, whose function was to supervise Tibetan
administrative affairs. China's sovereignty over Tibet was further
bolstered through the subsequent establishment of military
garrisons in the region during Emperor Yongzheng's reign, Ku Kuo
said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that China's sovereignty over Tibet is thoroughly
based on historical facts and cannot be legitimately denied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980112.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-01-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Pays Back 38 Billion Dollars of Foreign Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, January 11 (Xinhua) -- Brazil paid back a total of 38
billion U.S. dollars of foreign debts last year, 4.6 billion more
than the previous year, the Central Bank announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
They included 23 billion dollars of due capital and 15 billion
dollars of interest.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the country has to pay an estimated 30.6 billion
dollars of foreign debts this year, including 13.6 billion dollars
servicing.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, whose foreign debt totals 177.1 billion dollars, is the
number one debtor nation among the developing countries. The heavy
burden has been one of the major obstacles to its economic
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
