<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Economy Forecast to Perform Better in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The London-based influential
 Economic Intelligence Unit has predicted that New Zealand's
economy will grow 2.9 percent in 1998, higher than the 2.7
percent global average.
</P>
<P>
The unit was quoted today by the local newspaper The Dominion
as saying the weakening NZ dollar and tax cuts scheduled for July
will be bonuses for the economy while New Zealand should also
benefit from a more buoyant Australian economy.
</P>
<P>
It forecast that the growth will pick up to 2.9 percent from
1.9 percent in 1997 while inflation should remain low at 2
percent. The growth level will be even higher than the 2.4 percent
growth predicted by the unit for the Asia-Australia-New Zealand
region.
</P>
<P>
However, the unit warned that New Zealand's continuing high
foreign debt level poses the greatest threat to continued growth.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the current account deficit is expected to rise
to 5.3 percent of gross domestic product, the highest level in the
Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development.
</P>
<P>
"A small merchandise trade surplus will be overwhelmed by a
massive invisibles deficit of nearly 5 billion U.S. dollars,
almost entirely owing to the cost of servicing New Zealand's
forecast 61 billion U.S. dollars worth of foreign debt," the unit
noted.
</P>
<P>
"So far, financial markets have turned a blind eye to this
imbalance, but they may be unable to ignore it for much longer,"
it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
