<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, January 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers Monday:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- Indonesia was forced into crisis talks with the
International Monetary Fund Sunday night as President Soeharto
prepared for a crucial week in the fight for survival of his
government, which finally suspended costly projects.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- Australian university chiefs will be forced to recruit an
additional 45,000 local and overseas fee-paying students over the
next three years following the Australian government's decision to
freeze all future spending on higher education, official documents
reveal.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Indonesia has moved to restore its economic credibility by
dumping 15 infrastructure projects worth more than 6.4 billion
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
-- Pay increases won by unions are falling in most sectors of
the economy as low inflation, continuing high unemployment and a
tough new resolve by employers take the heat out of wage rises.
</P>
</TEXT>
